The book says there is a way to bear hug the left arete with micro crimps for V3 (#653) it also says there is a patina edge you can jump to then derp to the center plate for V4 (#654). I simply jumped all the way to the center plate. I did not see any micro crimps to bear hug... maybe next time i will bring a magnifying glass. But run and jump variation was fun, a little spicy at the top with sweaty hands and no pad but I've walked by this boulder so many times I'm glad I finally got on top of it.

Wow I enjoyed this. Instead of starting on the same small crimps at the back of the sloper as I did for "Irritable Bowel Syndrome" I put a low right heel toe cam in and started on the sloper itself. Pretty cool shuffly hand moves off the heel toe cam to big ol' holds.
Summer fitness on V1 as well! Honestly really fun, big ol' throw from jug to jug, then continue up jugs. I started climbing at 6pm today, 3 hours of fitness lets gooo!

#PRNF ([P]ending [R]eal [N]ame [F]ound) - This looks more like a stack of pancakes than the boulder literally named "Pancake House". The line I did is slightly contrived, start on the obvious side pulling jug and move right up the corner then reach right to a good hold on the right face and top out with a high ass left foot and a good under cling. 

This climb is right next to a cairn so I'm positive it has been done before, in fact, everything I'm logging today I'm pretty sure has been done. This area is "kind of" in the book, I quote: "Deer Canyon also has some bouldering at the far end of the canyon, and along the rim at the end of the canyon. Information was vague and it was elected not to be included" [Miramontes, pg.253].

#PRNF ([P]ending [R]eal [N]ame [F]ound) - Just walk up and right from Kinesthesia following things you think might be trails. This is a kind of aesthetic looking low angle slab right as you get to the ridge. Many variations probably exist but try to go as direct up the cleft as possible. Not like two planets but not completely lacking of erotic response.

This climb gets max points in the aesthetic category for its absolutely stellar shape and location. I mean this thing is just reeking of feminine beauty!! I could totally make half donkey/half dragon babies with this thing. It might be a little creepy but hey its love. 

It is slightly forced (you can easily rock over at basically any point) and rock quality isn't perfect (seems a little thin at parts and there is a friable chicken head which is easily avoided but definitely in the line). That all being said, this roof is absolutely ridiculous, full outward distance traveled from ground to tip is like 30ft or more; aaand somehow this rock is positioned right on the ridge with a gorgeous view westward toward Morongo. I mean this ridge is so iconic you can pinpoint it from the 10 freeway while driving to Tram. Topping out to a view like that is just ALL TIME.

#PRNF ([P]ending [R]eal [N]ame [F]ound) - Sit start on the left side of the face and do a cool right hand gaston high left foot move. Every hold above the 8 ft mark on this boulder is an absolute jug. So crazy.

#PRNF ([P]ending [R]eal [N]ame [F]ound) - Very cool looking formation. Literally looks like a Giant Granite Fist protruding out of the ground. Start on a juggy hold between the middle and pointer finger (pointer finger is the one actually sticking out), and right hand on a good opposing hold beneath the pointer finger. Make a wicked move the the over sized jug on the pointer finger and swing one armed for good measure. Be keen about it will ya! Then move left swinging feet into the dihedral for a stem top out! Rad. Make sure to avoid all rocks to the right of the pointer finger for full contrivance points.
The starting jug is cool. But I did not enjoy the climb overall.

#PRNF ([P]ending [R]eal [N]ame [F]ound) - on the left side of the boulder (it is just to the left of "Eigenvector"). Kinda compression like, kinda jug walk. Top out on the corner and make sure you knock on the top of the boulder when you get there. So crazy that the flat surface of the top of the boulder can sound so Hollow! It makes me wonder if I never had to but I'd better knock on wood.. er.. granite patina in this case.

#PRNF ([P]ending [R]eal [N]ame [F]ound) - Start low on a well oversize jug and put your balls to the wall, or whatever creative move you come up with to not dab and reach upward toward the better holds at the lip. Interesting movement with cool start hold. A stones throw north westward of Linear Algebra (that is an European stones throw, not to be confused with an African stones throw). So like 40 ft.

#PRNF ([P]ending [R]eal [N]ame [F]ound) - Start on the rightish side and just go upward. Jugs jugs jugs jugs jugs jugs jugs, juggy jugs!! This boulder I am dubbing the "Linear Algebra" boulder.. do the math.. it checks out.

Worth doing for the aesthetic of the boulder alone! The wavy ripples are so obvious and striking when walking up deer canyon. Climb is essentially an easy mantle followed by a half flight of stairs but I enjoyed myself.

#PRNF ([P]ending [R]eal [N]ame [F]ound) - On the ridge of deer canyon on your way to Diving Board there is a stellar face with tons of holds and variations. Try to follow the most obvious up-left trending crack on the center of the face. There are so many holds that its easy to drift one way or the other but keep it classy. 

NOTE: This recommend is for this boulder in general not specifically this line. If this boulder was closer to the Station it would be an ultra classic warm up location with variations of variations.

(#720, pg.259) - This climb was actually very fun! What I did, did not strictly follow the line in the guidebook; but I climbed the most obvious line I could see. Started on an obvious jug and pretty much went straight up from there. Top was kind interesting with under clings and smeary feet. Adventure mode. Just climb what looks cool!
(#727, pg.261) - Really good! All the holds are friendly, plenty of foot and beta options. I had a good warm up here. Too bad its so far away so no one will actually warm up here.
(#728, pg. 261) - Not as good as the V3 but worth doing if here. I had a pretty long internal debate if coming today would be worth it. My body is quite tired these days.

PRNF (Pending Real Name Found): So the Talus field that "Spaceship X" is in is actually quite large! With quite a bit of potential for some local choss climbing. If you are going to "Spaceship X" you hike the Service Trail (that is really obvious opposite the lower end of the school) for about 5 minutes, then "Spaceship X" will be on your left. BUTT if you go left, the talus field extends to eternity!!! There is a cluster of boulders fairly obvious once you start going up the talus the the next couple climbs are in this cluster. Nothing very tall or very good, but hell its close its choss and i climbed it.

This climb actually had Chalk on it!!! Start on a friable feeling uncercling/sidepull, pop a drop knee in and go to better holds. Maybe 7 feet tall.

PRNF (Pending Real Name Found): Just to the right of "Baldy Choss #17" there is another boulder with a large cool scoop/shelf and a lower jug. Start on the Jug and throw a big move up to the shelf and finish by pulling yourself up and left into the shelf.
PRNF (Pending Real Name Found): Same start as "Features for Breakfast" but make another big move up and right to the lip.

PRNF (Pending Real Name Found): There are quite a few lines on the slab face of the "Urushiol" Bolder but I only felt comfortable doing 2. Some of the rock is suspect but cool face. This like is the slab immediately left of the Sharp Arete. In fact to make if funner you can do the same sit start as "Urushiol" and rock around the corner if you so desire.
PRNF (Pending Real Name Found): The leftmost line on the slab face of the "Urushiol" Bolder. The ideal line would be straight up the middle of the slab but id like a real landing for that.

PRNF (Pending Real Name Found): If looking at "Features for Lunch" this climb is the arete on the right edge of the boulder. Its kind of tight since the "Squeeze me like one of your French Girls" is basically touching your right side. Start low and make a hard right hand move to a sharp crimp, then make another derpy move to a great left hand edge. Named in honor of the troglodytes who use this cluster as a nice drinking spot. I hope its not the elementary school kids.

PRNF (Pending Real Name Found): All in all the Mount Baldy area is amazing. The Mount baldy hike itself (up ski hut trail and down devils backbone) is top 3 hikes I have ever done in my life... and its so close!! Icehouse Canyon is also an amazing hiking area with a permanent crystal clear creak! How have I now treated myself to this incredible area before now. I cant wait to eat and some of the Diners in town too. I wanna get drunk. 

Dude, Mount Baldy is so insane that during winter months there is Goddamn Ice Climbing!! That's insane. Like 30 minutes from Upland there is Ice Climbing!? Really!? Calmer than you are Donnie.

Anyway, this climb starts the same place as "Uushiol" (and is named in such a way to help you pronounce "Urushiol") but goes straight up the sharp arete. Amazing.

PRNF (Pending Real Name Found): Pretty bad climb for such a cool PRNF. If you are sitting at "Features for Breakfast" look to your right. If you squint hard enough you may be able to imagine a line up the boulder. Start low on a left facing sidepull for your left hand and i think i remember a opposing crimp for my right. Do whatever the fuck you want but try to at least use the cool left hand pinch.
ascents.zlaggableName: Squeeze me like one of your French Girls

ascents.comment:
PRNF (Pending Real Name Found): Climbable boulders 17 minutes from Chelsea's House!! What!? The internet is incredibly vague with information of climbing in the Mount Baldy Area. Like it describes the 'Rock Garden" in the Baldy Bowl (which I will climb soon-all easy stuff), and a few areas with one or so mediocre climbable boulder. I think there was some friction with local landowners so its all been hush-hush. 

This area is actually called "Mount Baldy Hillside Boulders" on Mountain Project, but the entry trail starts immediately opposite the school so it feels way more self explanatory this way. The only climb listed in this area is "Spaceship X"... I actually never found "Spaceship X" this day, even though there is literally GPS coordinates on MP comments. Anyway, from some scoping a previous day I saw a boulder up the hill that looked like it had potential. I saw the remnants of what I thought might be a climber trail and took a peek. The trail quickly and completely disappeared but I pushed through some sharp Yucca and saw remnants of some old but unmistakable trail makings. There were obvious saw marks and moved branches that formed a kind of tunnel. It was vastly overgrown but I knew my destination and protected with a pair of high thigh board shorts and a Pickle Rick tank I proceeded to do the worst bushwhack I've ever done. Every plant was seeding so i was covered head to toe with all kinds of flora, the most interesting of which was this plant which had "wishie" looking pods that each had hundreds of hairy caterpillar looking seeds. Needless to say is was itchy, bleeding, dirty and excited as hell.

The boulder has an incredible aesthetic overhanging sharp arete, with a ~20' tall slab to the left and a maybe 30 degree overhanging face on the right. It has a bolt on top of the boulder. This climb starts sitting on the obvious arete but trends slightly right to holds on the overhang. With an insanely cool toe hook you span up to the end of the overhang and do some tension moves to finish. For how so-so the rock quality in the area in general this climb feels bullet! 

So I did describe how good the bushwhack was right? And how much clothing protection I had on right? Well, as I'm walking around the boulder, I see a plant I think I recognize and it triggers great fear. Poison Oak. And its goddamn everywhere. 

I'm still not 100% sure it was, but since that day I have been hyper sensitive to even the faintest itch in Great Fear that I will break out in the worst poison oak rash this world has seen. The oil in Poison Oak is called "Urushiol" and I PRNF dub this in the plants honor. Fuck Me.

This climb is actually in the book and is the original stand start to "Soul Shine". I have finally interpreted the description for this climb and it is a jump start. Start with your left hand in the ultra classic slot and jump for a variety of hold choices. The book says if you jump all the way to the Jug it is easier (ie not V6). I chose to jump to the Hueco you use for the "modern beta" of Soulshine. Still couldn't do the "OG" Soulshine beta that chase is revitalizing, so I am taking points for thsi stand! Boo yah.

Milk was such a bad choice. Feels like I'm climbing up a waterfall of Extra Virgin Olive Oil.

PRNF (Pending Real Name Found): What a hilarious misunderstanding. Oohh Ha haha ha. Nathaniel and I made a day trip to tram today! I told him "Whenever your little heard desires. As long as we leave before 3pm for traffic reasons". I meant that as long as we head TO the tram by 3pm, but in retrospect my wording is quite ambiguous. Nathaniel assumed i mean LEAVE the tram by 3pm. Pretty funny. Anyway we took second tram up, 10:10am. Railed by heat and frail bodies, it ended up being a good misunderstanding because we were very ready to leave by 3pm.

If at the Bush Pilot boulder looking at "The Pit and the Pendulum" this climb is the suspended boulder to the left. Starts on actually a pretty darn cool left hand hueco-y pinch feature and a jug for the right. Cool toes hooks and heel hooks on good holds lead to a surprisingly difficult top out! It might have been that Extra Virgin Olive Oil that was lathered all over the boulder but it took Gregor "top out master" Recian-God many tried to find beta to successfully mantle. Might be V5. 

Named for the words I was saying before I sent. "Burn, Baby Burn!.. Fucking Rock!" I scratched my back pretty good getting down to the sit start hence the "Fucking Rock" part.

This is two climbs to the right of Bikes and Trikes. Maybe a 1/3 cup or 3 tbsp. of fun, kinda surprising for a no star campus. I think its given V0 in the book but V0 with mandatory campus? huh. The V2 to the right of this looks wack.

(# , Pg) - I will add # and Pg when i get back to my trusty guide book. This is the jug line to the right of Bikes and Trikes. Easy peezy. Nate the Psyche Monster is hilarious. We should call him positive feedback phenomenon, if hes psyched his psyche is infinite. But if he starts to lose psyche.. absolute zero my dudes. lol. Hope he keeps psyche into the actual climbing season.

PRNF: I want you to take this moment to remember the worst place you have ever forgotten your keys. You imagining it? Well now imagine this: You finish a 14 mile out and back, 4300' elevation gain hike, go to unlock your car, and are suddenly struck by a vivid memory of your keys sitting atop a lonely rock at the very tip of Ontario Peak. What would you do? A better question is what would Gregor do? Ill tell you. 

Gregor would promptly turn around and do the hike AGAIN!!! The sun set LONG before I reached the peak, so i very unsafely was hiking by myself in the Cucamunga Wilderness, no light, limited water, and tired as hell. I was singing loudly the entire time to ease my growing fears of being mauled by a demigorgon. Luckily the moon came up to give me a little light, and luckily my water only ran out with 2 miles left. I may be an idiot, but luckily I'm a fit idiot otherwise i may have died.

All in all i did 28 miles of hiking, 8600' of elevation gain in 7 hours and 30 minutes.

PRNF: Pretty casual Approach. 7 miles and 4300' elevation gain. I read online that there was a boulder at the actual Peak so I hiked with my climbing shoes and trusty Totoro chalk bag. I was pleasantly surprised with the boulder that awaited me. It was WAAAAY taller than i expected. Way sketch this far out. So sketch in fact that I only ended up doing 2 lines of like a potential 6 or so lines. This one goes up the Class 4 Baldy side slab of the boulder. Easy but very asethetic views. 

The king line would definitely be the south face. A good 20'+ and very gorgeous looking line. I climbed about 10 feet up on great holds, but was not willing to commit without better protection.

PRNF: So again I tried to find "Spaceship X". I eventually found it, but only after [I] endured blistering winds and scorching deserts - [I] climbed the highest bloody room of the tallest bloody tower - and what d[id] [I] find? Some gender-confused WOLF telling [me] that [MY] princess is already married! Turns out you have to turn left off the trail slightly before the obvious talus field through a subtle yet plush crease in the foliage (no poison oak here luckily). I walked through more during that desert montage though. If you are trying to find "Spaceship X" for the first time just have your GPS up the entire time. Don't be a fool.

This climb is just to the left on the downhill face when you hit the obvious talus field. Start of the very friable jug and move up and right.

PRNF: If there was no dabber rock this climb would have been dubbed differently. It also would be awesome! Jug with low big feet to a awesome large incut crimp! Perfect distance. Took three tries to not dab, had to use all 7 abs I got.
ascents.zlaggableName: Just a Hop, Skip and a Dab Away

ascents.comment: PRNF: Start as for "Baldy Choss # 5" but pull directly outward really hard. If it breaks you get V5 and congrats your and asshole.  No but do start on the same jug but reach out left to a small crimp then super bump to good holds up and left on the lip. Thought this would be V0 so shame on me when it felt like i ripped my tricep without warming up.

PRNF: So he can fit in his spaceship.....

Anyway, stand start. Looks like there is a slightly lower start at a grade or two harder and maybe a super low at like way harder. Anyway, the right hand start is obvious, its a right facing decent hold toward the right side of the "Spaceship X" boulder. The left hand goes on some slimper to oppose it. Campus yer feet up to a sweet toe hook on the right arete and cross, then send away dear boy! I cant believe i finally found "Spaceship X"!! pretty amazing to have this boulder so close!!
PRNF: Start as for "The Penny Pincher" but move left on some underclings + slab and over a slightly spicy landing.
PRNF: As implied by the name, this is a dyno if you are still in the egg, or i guess the womb counts too. This is a easy "dyno" about 8 feet to the left of "Young Oblio".
PRNF: Mount Baldy's Best Kept Secret Slab #1. Pretty large cool boulder. If on the back side this is the left of the two slabs. GPS (34.228458, -117.666598)
PRNF: Mount Baldy's Best Kept Secret Slab #2. Pretty large cool boulder. If on the back side this is the center slab. GPS (34.228458, -117.666598)

PRNF: Holy Roley Poley Mr. Guacamole! This wall is unreal. Sustained overhang with decent height and cool features! Some of the rock (especially up high) is suspect but damn this rock is cool. This line, which I am dubbing "Mount Baldy's Best Kept Secret" is the right side of the large overhanging face up a almost prow. Holds all feel nice and movement is good. Even has option of a lower extension if you wanted to get a workout here. Want to com back to work the other, harder lines!
PRNF: On same boulder as "The Penny Pincher". South side I believe. Easy face. The valley shadow in my video creates a very trippy illusion with the background mountains.

PRNF: The starting pinch is to die for. If I am wealthy enough in the future, I will make all my door knobs in my house have be molded to this exact shape. 

Follow the natural angle up and right and get rewarded with a beautiful Baldy valley view! Located higher talus.

PRNF: Doesn't it suck when you are the only round headed person in the Pointed Village and by law everyone and everything must have a point!? Yeah me too. This thing has a really nice back drop and goes up a pretty cool point feature. Must top out at the point for full points. heehee. This is in the deeper talus field. So after turning right of the main trail, trundle up and left a bit then straight a bit. 5-10 minutes off the main trail.

Not the most inspiring line, but it has some features and its always good to have more easy stuff in an area. I believe it is located two tiers below [Ze Paump] on a corner. Dont worry eventually ill make a guide......

Not a very tall boulder but cool moves and surprisingly difficult top out with not so great fall potential. The starting move is DOPE, you have a sloper meat hook thing for your left and and a good incut for your right and you simply throw up a right heel, lock off to a crimp, then bust to the lip!

I think there is a harder variation where you start further right and lock up left hand but I couldn't do it. 

Located on the tier beneath Mushroom Poppy Project. Named because during this time of year there were berries EVERYWHERE. I wish i knew what was not poisonous so i could nom nom. Also worth noting, I accidentally left my brush I bought in [Fonatinbleau] at [Tea Rex] during mid June... I was fairly certain I knew where i left it, but it was incredibly satisfying to come back 3 months later and find it buried in tons of wild raspberries!.

This is the slab that starts the same Start Jug as [Ze Paump] but instead of following the natural line up and left make a lock off right and quest up the slab. For your enjoyment: The Governator in his prime
ascents.zlaggableName: DEH MOZT ZATYSFYIN FEELING YOU CAN GHET

ascents.comment:
The distinguishable features are the ramp like bulge and the orange lichen. It would be so amazing is there was a static way to do this, but as it is it is a run and jump!! Try to stay true and follow the thin orange line, but on the FA I was slightly right.

On the opposite side of the road is a MASSIVE boulder which may have potential if you clean off centuries of moss...

Same boulder as [Elder Wand]. Start far right on a huge foot ledge. Finagle your way left through a hold facing the wrong way to get on the the amazing arete/lip. Traverse ALL the way through the apex till you can through your left heel over the left side of the boulder. You can easily rock over tons of times before the apex, but that is no fun and not the full line. If you do bail early I will know, and I will award you no points.

Despite being contrived, very good climb.

A slightly harder variation on "Portabella". Instead of moving directly up, do a reach out right to a very nice feeling incut seam. Then bust a big left hand move to the most scooped part of the lip and please, throw in a foot swing even if your feet stayed, just for good measure.

Very stupid but I wanted to establish something on the steepest part of the roof and this was all I could manage. That beings said, [very stupid] = [very fun]. 

Start with left hand on the jug rail and right hand on a pad sized incut undercling on the roof. The span here is ridiculously large and depending on your wingspan this is either not doable or too easy. Also depending on wingspan you have to choose which part of the Jug rail works best for you. 

Since the span is so large and the overhang steep, as soon as you pull off the ground your body wants to swing outward toward the jug. You make a desperate campus slap from the undercling to a slopy feature to stop your swing then do one more campus to the next jug. 

Supe mega ultra classic must do!

A rock I've looked at as we drive by for years. I knew it was small, and looked chossy but it always had an alluring overhang. Sure enough, its Chossy! Well the starting blocks don't looks super sturdy, but nothing flexed. There are tons of good holds so just make your way up. 

Location, if you know where that little flower pond is that has "shooting stars" this is a bend or two down the road on the uphil side.

Wow. Definitely didn't expect this to be so much fun! Gave me similar vibes as "Auto Body" up in Squamish, just waaay easier, annnd waaaay more itty bitty living space. In other words, very Hobbit sized. Walking up to the boulder its not that tall but there is a pretty cool hole that goes under the boulder. There is a huge crack underneath with perfect start jugs which turn into perfect toe hooks as you round the lip. Because its Hobbit sized, dabbing potential is there but it makes the tension and toe hooks sweeter. Surprisingly one of the hardest moves is after you have rounded the lip and have right hand on the arete jug. It is SOOO hard to get the final right foot up. A lot of vey nice feeling holds and good sequence around the lip.

Solo trip to MK baby!! Cant believe I keep finding new good stuff at Cold Springs! I also found a new path into the main bounder field which doesn't require bush wacking. Simply go up the right side of the boulderfield (Faint trail above campsite 12) until you see this climb, or The Hobit Hole. Quite easy but could serve as a good warm up. 

Aptly named because I walked through a couple flowers what were sending their progeny out into the world. Hundreds of wishie seeds flew all around me and finally up into the sky where they made thousands of wishes come true.

To the right of [DEH MOZT ZATYSFYIN FEELING YOU CAN GHET V1] there is another easier slab you can climb. This is that easier slab. Thank you Matthias for sharing the amazing clip of Our Beloved Governator which inspired these names.

How did I miss this boulder all these years! Its huge and glorious! So many amazing features on the lip and it looks like potential for some harder lines/variations as well. The roof this lip on is like 60 degrees overhanging! I don't think the overhang is possible, but there are some not so good holds that might be shark toothed in nature... so who knows. Drewbie? 

It's pretty amazing that the full lip is actually the path of least resistance. There might be a way to mantle early but it would definitely be harder than V7. 

I started on the pretty obvious underling feature with a good incut.

Aptly named for the seemingly likely potential of falling and getting very, very wet. Took me several times of pulling on to finally commit to the big move. The rock on this piece feels AMAZING.

Just beneath the main "waterfall", if you look eastward toward the waterfall this boulder is overhanging the main creek on the right. It has dab potential directly behind you and the water beneath is a few feet deep! Even getting to the start holds was a little annoying because you have to lean across some water to grab a nice left and right edge, then stretch your foot over to avoid getting wet. Then you pull on and you are in it.

Also probably not an FA, but again info is quite vague. On the same boulder as "Scylla". Start as low as you can to make the most out of this little arete. The rock is so smooth here and its often in the sun so quite easy to take a bouldering whipper. Its also impossible to pad since you would be dabbing always. Still had a fun move or two which make it worth doing!

*The second piece of a idiom based in Greek mythology meaning "Between a Rock and a Hard Place"
Meh. Small but it is in the shade and start features are well at least features... its best feature is that its close to "Mr. Longarm"

Finally trying to climb at Rancho Penasquitos Canyon! I've wanted to for years but there's not that much and it just seemed like activation energy was too high. But now that I've found the catalyst I think i might make a regular thing out of it! There is nothing AMAZING, but there is enough low ball stuff i could run out without a pad, climb some stuff an make a workout out of it!

Started just beneath the ball since there were jugs beneath the ball.
Not on the right, not on the left.. somewhere in the middle. Start with butt on ground, a good undercling/sideulll for the left and a down pulling crimp for the right. Climb straight up!

Start as for Face Climb but move left to the arete and climb it like that. Very nice. I got my first reaction to Poision Oak a few months ago when i was scoping the area.. be careful! Especially in spring/early summer!

Actually moderately entertaining. Start as for 'Face Climb' traverse all the way tight to top out on the right side of the  boulder. 

So in order to prevent myself from climbing too long I intentionally did not bring any food or water. Pretty smart huh? Once you get too hungry (or thirsty whatever happens first) then its time to go. Genius! 10 / 10 will do again...

... when i got back home i had lost 5 pounds... in 4 hours... 

Still would do again!
Start butt on ground on far right side of the boulder. Do some moves on jugs. Not very good, but it is climbing.

Definitely a must do for the area. One very fun move on a very obvious boulder. I am very hungry and thirsty at this time. Maybe next time I should bring food or water?

nah.

A nice climb anywhere! Definitely one of the main attractions for the area. Big ol' move to a nice hold. Will likely do this climb many more times in my life time. In a nice spot of perpetual shade! except maybe deep, deep summer...

Probably not an FA, but info is vague enough.  If looking  North-West from "Still Waters Run Deep" you  can see this awesome looking two part boulder that was split eons past to from a large triangle like wedge between the halves. In the open wedge, on the left side of the face is a hand crack which is not just climbable, but fun and painful to boot! Because you are climbing in the space between two boulders padding is kind of hard but the crack is super rad. The rock quality is great since its so close to the water too. 

*The first piece of a idiom based in Greek mythology meaning "Between a Rock and a Hard Place"

Also probably not an FA. Been playing too much Stardew Valley so I couldn't resist the mineral reference. Quite fun with optional toe hooks. Start sitting with left hand in an undercling in the horizontal crack feature and right hand wherever.

Definitely need your head screwed on tight for this one! Scope it out because the fall would not end well. But that being said its very easy and the rock is the most striking feature on the south side of the creek. When you are on the North Side looking over, this climb just sings. Kuzco could build his summer home here. 

Also note that the right side of this boulder has potential for an amazing ~v6 FA. Amazing holds lead to either a terrifying roll onto "Where Eagles Dare" or a cool looking sequence up and right. Hopefully I can snag this FA in the next week.

Start on the right side of the small overhang (South-West corner). Find some way to hold your left hand as an under-cling and right hand on a small crimp just above the overhang. I wanted to start matched on the undercling feature but life is hard. One powerful move to a good right hand edge then finish up "SW Overhang"

Felt so hard at first! Took me several burns to even find the secret holds. Feels a little contrived to bail out of the standard Hangnail Left, but fun technical face climbing that was a fun puzzle to work through. When I finally figured out the beta I ran it back a few times for footage. The gaston move is rhetorical.

"Well, not today, pal!" Wanted to climb this for the aesthetics in a potential climbing video. Its a nice large boulder that is very photogenic and iconic for the area.... but its a ginormous piece of CHOSS!! Still fun but on my send go I pulled off a 5-10lb hold that plummeted right between my feet! Moderately terrifying but I didn't fall so i figured, 'huh, well I bet the rest of the boulder is good'.
ascents.zlaggableName: Im a crumbling canyon wall & Im taking you with me

ascents.comment:
Not as good as I thought it would be. I've looked at this boulder extensively over the years, and because it has some awesome features i figured it would easily be the best climb of the area. I mean its good, but you know what i really want. 

The big jugs are too sharp to be comfortable, the start was not as intuitive (I may have started low...), and the top was a little awk. 

It is forever in the shade so, thats a big plus, and it still looks cool. If you are in the area it is still a must do, but like an over-hyped movie, i had my hopes too high.

I loved this one. Would be better without a dabber rock but fun lock-offs! Mountain Project has a similar climb called 'South Face' which may start in a similar location, but that climb uses the arete.. boo! 

This version starts on the obvious seam with a high left heel, gets the cool left hand face crimp then locks up right hand to a good enough hold just below the lip. Hard not to dab but fun!
All good holds, right next to the water, on the shady side of things. Dab potential is annoying but a decent line all in all. People were watching me climb this one!
Most likely not an FA. Start as for Still Waters Run Deep, but after a move or two fire big out of the crack to a good hold at the lip.
Not as nice, but still nice, and still short. I think I may make a pretty nice extensive circuit out here!

Could be an FA, but probably not. Start as for Still Waters Run Deep, but go up and right through a few cool crimps instead! My favorite line on the boulder actually. On my first go attempt my heel popped and I fell into the water
Very nice. Quite short.

Tried it in my cruisers, Nick told me i couldn't do it, I was inclined to believe him, but then the thought of putting my shoes on was too much to bear so i just finished it. 

One of the largest loose, but not going anywhere holds is on this climb.

Never heard of this before but will add it to the amazing must do V4s at tram. Ill start spreading the word. 

The starting feed are a little crumbly (that will clean up) but very nice crack with good holds and you get a glorious top out! The book says "Funky landing" but with one pad i felt as snug as a bug in a rug.

I wish I remembered my guide book so I could have snagged all the obscure lines on this boulder. There are some classics like "Fire' Farts", "It's another route", "Dynamo Hum", "The 19th hole" and "the crumbly route"! I really missed out. Next time baby!
Meh. Hopefully we don't miss Marina coming down the trail!
When your nips need a little trim, why not try this?

Rather interesting, would never recommend, and never thought i would ever try, yet here we are. The entire crux revolved around a very tenuous left foot smear with desperate slaps for the top. Hey look ma i made it!
Surprisingly good. Left most climb on the slot machine boulder. Now all I have left on this boulder is "Real mans Problem". I wonder if anyone ever tries that thing.
Probably not an FA. Start as for "Yardarm of the Tram" (#65, pg. 43 of the guide). But move left left through some gaston-y crimp features to eventually rejoin "Yardarm of the Tram". Obscuro-man!

Snagging some points for my car while the big boys work Holy Rails. 

Actually quite nice! I really want to try the 6 next door too. Proud of AK for "BAHT"-ing super loud on his send burn. 

If there wasn't a gorgeous sunset happening simultaneously, Marina would have crushed this thing. Something that gorgeous and pink is calling your name is just too damn distracting. But also time pressure does not help one bit.

This boulder is glorious! I mean, hehe, its in the name! But seriously, walking up to this thing is always inspiring, and what better people to walk with than people you like! 

Shout out my friends: Chase 'no longer girthy' Yamashiro, Scott 'ill have a sip later' Baron, Akhil 'Johnson' Mauze, Drew 'who's on drew duty' Gomberg, Marina 'im sorry we missed that sunset' Marlens, Michael 'Chase in your Wallet' Homer and Jaquie 'see you in another few years' Ngyuen.


There may have been a little bit of a love tap from Drewbie on the send burn, but like nobody said ever: never look a gift horse in the mouth. Plus if you cant accept love when freely given, life might be terribly dreary indeed! 

Great weekend, great people, and ill drink to that.

I had to check but there is literally a programming language called "DICK" and every function MUST be declared as "8=+>(){}" where the "+" is to indicate that any number of '=' signs may be used. Furthermore every variable must be defined as [<=+8]. Holy shit i cant believe that's real. 

Regardless good climb. Crux mantle? easier in cruisers, trust me.
Meh. Its got a bad landing... who doesnt!!

Gregor "grease gun" Recian-God, patiently waited his turn before splooshing all over this one. That high seam was way worse than i thought it would be and i left it worse than that even. I bet you cant even imagine. I cant and i was THERE. Sorry folks. I might be the sole reason drew doesn't have SteelFingersV8Soft. 

That high seam seems like it would be better and that nub nabbles like a champ. #alliteration #homophone

I have two shout outs:
#1 Marina for saying goodbye to rational thought and hello to simply sending shit!! When you get past the crux all that matters is sending, way to go! I was 10 billion percent (reference anyone?) sure that you would not fall.
#2 SteelFingersv8Soft - You bring smiles to many and I hope you have a nice winter season. You are a real hero and deserve a nice warm hearth to roast chestnuts at. If I hear you spent the winter alone I will drive out and warm you myself. Cheers.
Points baby! We never did an official tally but pretty sure Me Chase and Marina pulled the 'W'.

Same greasy hold, same solution: Throw a far high heel! After barely doing "Lost but not forgotten i 'fear and loath'ed that this would be beyond me, but turns out it is significantly softer, especially with the heel.  Tried Chases and Scott's beta but both need too much crimp power on the right hand. In case i didn't properly tell you how wet the hold was in my lost comment....  it was so wet you could see the surface tension of water.

For how close this is to Holy Rails I cant believe no one does it... well i guess drew broke holy rails so no one comes here anymore.. 

AMAZING mantle on this bad boy. I had a nice flip from Meat Hook to Monkey Grip. Very nice. Ill drink to that. Scott? Will you drink with me, or you still need to wait till later?

Is this still V8 after Gregor 'Grease Gun" Recian-God gets on it? I rocketed off that hold so many times and even Shirley "This thing is so easy" Girth was having a hard time. Im so greasy even Marina had to admit to my insurmountable power of slip.  

Hardest thing I tried all trip by far. I had to throw a very high right heel as early as possible to take as much weight off my hands as possible since shoes don't sweat. Hands do. 

That being said, this boulder really is a nice boulder. So glad I didn't have to admit that Nate-Bro is stronger than me today.

Haven't had a good send train in a while. It fees good Chase, it feels good. And ill drink to that. Cant believe drew did the top of the climb easier than i did. And ill drink to that. Also shout out to good times underneath Stones Throw, breaking shells and being crude. Some things always seem weirder as a third person... but if the work they work. Thanks Scott! And ill drink to that.

Pretty sure this is "Reach for it Center" in the book but Reach for it center is just so many less characters! And i know that this is the best of the Reach For Its from experience... i mean i haven't tried the others but i know... you know?

And i would rather be listed with my precious 'Ryan Bauer' and 'Shirley Girth' than be politically correct.

Also WTF I biffed the big move one, this took more burns than Cellulite.
Very nice feature, our beta involved a pogo which fit the theme of very nice! Marina and AK both showing me up!!

That rad unnamed v6 on the pwyiack boulder. Quite nice. I was not as drunk as chase when he did it, nor did i have as few pads, and no i did not do it in cruisers.... maybe ill be cool some day. 

This should have a name because its nice. And nice things deserve names.
Pywiack V3. Warming up.
One of those slabs directly across Warm up roof. #5 page 223 from Moby Dick by Herman Melville.
ZE TIME WINDOW UTER!!!! EVERYBODY STOP DANCING, THE TIME WINDOW IS CLOSING!!!! UUUUTTTTEEEEERRR!!!!!
no chalk? no problem. 1-800-GREASE4LIFE.
Jugs, i like jugs. NEver forget.
Fun. Nice under cling start hold. Felt quite easy. I think an extension moving left instead of up could make this quite hard.

Definitely an area must do! Nothing too hard at the waterfall so it was nice to try rather hard on this one. Eileen and Chel (and Princess Ella - who loves my crash pad shade) ran out here with me for a quick sesh before a long sesh of drinking wine, beer, sake and meads!  Started on a low right hand crimp and a higher left hand side pulling crimp. Big first move to bomber right hand then, surprisingly hard sequence moving left. Bottom rock quality is great, but once you get through the crux it gets a bit hollow. Its located on the big rock on the north side of the waterfall. Same rock as Mr. Longarm just opposite side.

Not a flash since I failed the top out 8 years ago when I apparently couldn't even climb V0. It was M-Flash though,  which is nice. 

When I say "Ill bring the beers"... I bring the beers.
If this is V5, then relatively speaking, the stand must be easier the VB. However if the stand is V4, then relatively speaking, this must be V9. Ergo, grades don't make sense. QED

Despite this climb being quite amazing, its also not amazing in many ways. And while the old me would probably recommend this at the drop of a hat, I am changing my slutty ways (recommend slut that is). 

Bottom looks crumbly, and boulders hate crack, but that top move though... so so good. Is there a way to just recommend the top move on 8a?

Apparently this thing was V7 for 30 years [1]. Now with a guidebook saying V6 I can confidently give it V7 soft. Very cool! This was on my list of "I better do today otherwise... well shucks", so I was very glad to bring a pencil and a checkbox. The other climb on the "I better do today otherwise... well shucks" list was Sword of Damocles... which i did not do. Well, Shucks [1] Kody "Black Mountain Shutt"

"Very cool" formation, "Very cool" moves, "Very cool" landing.  

Overall, i must say: "Woah"

When you don't climb V12 this is the only way to enjoy this glorious boulder!!! So awesome!!

Immediate exposure with quality rock and climbing all the way. I just wish I would have remembered to climb with a beer so I could have stopped part way to take a sap. Only 4 beers short boys.

I actually do not know if I should consider this a flash... The book says climb for a while then rock over wherever.. which i did... but it is like way more aesthetic and fulfilling to go all the way to the tip. And even if I did rock over too early I reversed back into the climb... so I never came off. Ill take the flash.

I don't think more fun was ever had at this boulder, nor do I think there ever will be. We had an A+ cast of Drew, Kody, me, AK, and Chase and that turned out to be a recipe for greatness. 

Upgrading to Blue. Not Blue Tag mid you. Just Blue. Movement was actually the most redeeming quality. Watch you elbow!! Those 1-mph collisions can cause serious trauma!

I think another 100 laps and this may clean up enough to be nice.

Shitty climb with maybe a redeeming quality or two. 

A corner located about a football field west and slightly uphill of the really cool ultra secret don't tell anyone project Kody found. I tried to start lower but feet kept breaking so I just started on the obvious chossy hold.

Just west of Kody's cool ultra secret project that no one knows about lives this beauty. Its not very tall, there is a lot of choss, the middle scoop was dripping wet + full of green moss, but it is beautiful nonetheless. 

Start on the low right scoop and move left into the main set of scoops. Much harder than i expected but maybe when the center trench dries and is clean there will be some nice new holds.

A pretty fun move from a jug rail to the lip and a mantle. I never want to forget my good friend Kody. Thanks for getting off your lazy, sick ass to have fun with us today. Just to clarify to the audience, Kody in his entirety wasn't sick, just his ass. 

I think this is like 4-5 minutes uphill from the ultra cool super secret project Kody found. Problem faces up hill.

I want to log this now, but AK hasn't named it yet so this will have to do for now. This boulder has some serious potential. Amazing looking dragon talons scratched the left side of the boulder. But this climb is the simple uphill face following the obvious vertical crack. So many jugs much nice.

This boulder is ginormous, like really-really well endowed. Very big pin-pin, if you will. This boulder is just uphill from the super mysterious "Land Survey Monument - Please do not disturb" sign seemingly in no mans land. Maybe I am a recommend slut... but this climb is too good to abstain.  

"Pont du Gard" is on the uphill side and starts on the most obvious feature ever. Amazing ascending jug crack/trough that trends up and right. So many jugs, and just good climbing overall. This is also the down climb since every other part of the boulder is like 25+ feet. 

I would honestly be pretty surprised if this is real FA, the climb just sings so I'm sure someone else heard it before me.

I am a firm believer in always having fun when climbing. No matter how shitty the movement, how chossy or how contrived, all climbing should be fun. This climb made me doubt my mantra. 

Just kidding. I had fun. I always do. But damn i may have ruined the rest of my day with the heinous pump. M-soft-first go, and topepd out at the pipe for full value. Unless the pipe is not the accepted finish... in that case i didnt even do the climb.
I believe this was FA'ed by Famous Amos, right Kody? I am very proud to have finally found and sent Famous Amos's Heinous Anus!!

This climb really is fantastic. I think it took 4 sessions so pretty close to redlining. And it only took me 23 tries today; I know the exact number since I have footage. Piece of cake!

Also WTF this climb is so hard, i dont understand. My fat sausages are oozing more than ever before so i just kept rocketing out of that dirty sloot. Was trying to do that steezy had foot match lock off for the first 15 goes but i just got too tired and the hold got too greasy. So i had to settle for pogo. Still cool, but def not steezy!

Also, of everything i touched today the easiest climb was "Street Car Named Desire", i repeated it cause i was in the area. Although now that i think of it my palms dont sweat... only my tips. Bummer. Who do i complain to to fix that genetic defect?

Simply amazing. More climbs like this please. So nice I did it 5 times. Cant believe it was my 7th trip to JTree before I  finally touched this piece. 

I just landed a job in San Diego, and I start on December 9th so I wanted to get one last climbing trip under my belt. Was originally planning on going to bishop but too much rain my dudes. Got so stoked on JTree i just bought a guide and a national parks pass.

In this episode of "The Rock Whisperer", Fry Problem tells Gregor that she enjoyed his company and would like to meet up same time next week to share a pot of tea and talk about my first day of work. Super nice lady. She is also gorgeous and climbs quite nice too. Maybe a little bit of a stiffy, but I know she is soft at heart.
This was very nice! Basically two slab mantles, quite balency! Although I guess balency is not a word sooooo very body position dependent?

This felt super hard but pretty sure that was just my body, and my oozers of course. 

I originally came to Cap Rock because I wanted to do "All Washed Up" and "Pumping Monzonite" but this thing told me in bold faced all cap letters: YOU ARE WEAK. Thank you climb, thank you. Yes, when I am alone I speak to the boulders. This one is not very nice.

Either my body warmed up and slowed its volumetric flow rate out of my tips, or this thing is actually easier than that V3 by "All Washed Up". Quite nice though. Even tough its just a number, it felt good to at least do one new V6 this trip. I feel like i tried hard enough to deserve at least V7 forthe trip as a whole, but i dont think it works that way. At least i can enjoy analyzing the stats on betterThan8aDotNu.nu

Beautiful pinch!! Did I mention I forgot to bring water to Joshua Tree? Like just completely forgot. It wasn't a problem though i never even got thirsty once!! Well i did have a can of coffee and a fresh bell pepper so I'm sure that that was plenty. 

I actually saw a Nature Trail Sign at Cap Rock that said "Plants and Animals in the desert have adaptations to survive in this low water environment. Could you survive? What are your adaptations?".... I think i might behave found my family.

This sit was way more inspiring than the stand in my opinion. It just felt like this is what the setter wanted. I know this to be true because I talked to the rock and he said: "I am a sit not a stand, what don't you people get about that!? Where is my good buddy Yabo, I haven't seen that boy in years."

He warmed up to be after a while and thought my beta was quite nice. I used a super strong left toe to pull into a left hand gaston and cross it up. Pretty dope. Barely held the V1 stand move on the send go. Nothing like desperate V1 to sweeten your coffee in the morning.

Surprisingly fun. Didn't see this noted in the book, but it had chalk and was nice. Right as you walk into the Sandy Wash (with All Washed Up) this is on your right. Climbed the right side of the arete on bad feet. 

Might not be in the book because its class 4, but I am logging it.

This boulder is awesome. Like that jug right before the famed slopey lip encounter is just one of the most amazing features ever!! So ergonomic and so so concave. 

After hearing so much about this climb I was honestly a little nervous that i would blow the flash. I mean Nate flashed it! and he just sent AcidWashV10! Turns out the top out is cake.

Not a good climb, but I did flash so it must be like a super hero soft. Too bad i cant give it multiple softs. Need to help my softness rating. 

I will admit I used a knee to help bump my right hand. Pretty nifty i must say. As soon as my palms get on the rock im unstoppable.
Actually nice shorter version of weekender. Didn't know this was kosher.

Last climbing trip before fun-employment ends. Sad in many regards and happy in others. Having money will be nice. 

Should have m-flashed. Ran a warm up burn, to well, warm up and it felt like piss. Missed the jug on that jump because i didn't remember it being so soft. Then my fingers remembered they like to ooze and it got exponentially harder. Still sent, but I was genuinely afraid. 

Good to see my boy Nate. He been done living the live lately.

Like a tiger earns its stripes, this climb earned its 'hard'.

If I could make a hypothetical rock garden where i just choose rock climbs that are perfectly replicated so i could do them daily, this climb might make the cut. Even a 'might' is a big deal.

I hate that I am a recommend whore, but when you find a cute climb gruesomely curb stomped and left in the gutter, what would any kind soul do? That's right, you help her out.

This climb, while potentially chossy at the top (no big deal since its only class 3 climbing), it has an awesome gaston lock off (at least the way I did it). Since ive been to bishop tons of time and have never heard of this climb, i feel like the world (well at least my watchers) should at least hear of it. 

There are certainty better sixes but it deserves a look at least and maybe a fondle. Its just to the left of Morning Dove so its not far!
ascents.zlaggableName: Take the Force of the Blow

ascents.comment:
Ignacio Sandoval Burón you sweet sweet boy. I am glad you did not die on your endeavor. I am also glad I did not die, on my endeavor. Although at no point did i ever fear for my life and for that I am sorry.  

Truth be told this climb probably took me 20-30 burns over 3 sessions. How is that possible? on a climb with a possible quadriplegic or death fall? Well, I knew this thing was choss at the top, you don't kill people you dont know, thats a rule. Another rule is you scope the top out of dangerous high balls. 

Anyway, I did this climb incrementally one move at a time down climbing between every forward progression. I only pulled on the choicest choss to avoid increased odds of death.

It actually felt like V1 today and the only possibly sketchy hold is the one 25 feet up. No big deal. As long as you pull out not down you good. 

I think this was my first triple fluttering heart! I may repeat this.

It was okay. And with that I will use this extra space to talk about everything else from the trip not already in a comment.
  • Great to see Nate out here! Since I start work next week I was just gonna go solo but very nice to share sends and beers with a good friend!
  • I forgot to mention that everything in bishop is easier than everything in JTree. I tried so so hard in Jtree and only managed V5, then come here and with thin oozing skin do V > 5
  • I also did not bring any water to bishop. Unfortunately too because I am losing fitness not carrying around a never drank gas station gallon
  • While I did not have water this weekend, I did have expired Premier Protein shakes, vanilla flavor! While I am sure chemicals in a tetra pack don't ever actually expire, and the taste was still on par, it was like drinking cottage cheese. I could imagine some lesser stomachs gagging and the chunky grimy texture but I think I might be learning to like it.
I forgot to log this. Pretty obscure and took me a good 6 burns or so to actually try.

I enjoyed this WAY more than I expected. A V3* traverse, into a no hands rest, into a V5* crux sequence? The numbers certainty don't add up, but we knew it was soft anyway.

I was quite tired from the week so did not think i had any juice left (unless by juice you mean finger tip ooze, in which case i still had plenty) so I was just working the beta so I could m-Flash it next time. But then I found the super plush and very comfortable no hands rest, which was both wildly enjoyable and dramatically increased the softness.

I had never properly read the name of this climb before: "Pappa" "Chubby", basically Fat Daddy. Pretty funny name. 

*grades are a construct

I am always surprised when I go to an area I have been to a million times and there are still obscure lines I haven't done! This thing was surprisingly good movement wise, but I guess its made up of mostly choss. 

Carlos and Nate watched from below apparently with a fair amount of terror as I proceed to climb this thing and shower the pads with choss. Id really didn't feel that bad to me. I mean feet felt chossy but all the hands felt solid. Anyway, for those of you who love to obscure chase after me, this is the line to the right of Standing Kill Order! You reach up from the ramp rock to a square blocky hold and climb up!

Very cool seeing Carlos again. Still an incredible human. I just purchased his book on Amazon and it should arrive tomorrow. "The Void Within" by Carlos Tkacz.
To my glee, I accidentally did this when chalking up and checking durability of the holds for 'Push It'. Free ascents baby!

One of those climbs that you only do because the rock kinda loos pretty. It really is quite a pretty looking feature I swear! The rock goes from a chossy reddish at the top to a bullet smooth greenish at the bottom. The bottom also has a lot of water sculpted features including one of those big pit like holes that you start in. Starting this is funny because the ground is part of the same rock so kinda impossible not to flash.

Toward the western edge of lower falls area there is a jumble of rocks that has some really cool features. This is probably the least cool of those features but it is in the recess created by the three or so enclosing boulders. Start below the angle change of the obvious crack in the water sculpted bucket thing. Do easier moves than you though possible and then do the easiest mantle you have imagined... then reverse it to do it again in an even easier way if thats possible.

I saw chalk here!! yay! other climbers. This thing was quite easy, and it does have some suspect rock but it goes! Its rather obvious on the north side of lower falls. I started sitting as low as I could to make 1ml more of lemonade.

Quick date hike out here with the bae <3. Amazingly, a buffet was just sitting here!! Nice-su!

Anyway this has probably been done but start low on the prominent shelf and go straight up through the second shelf. Ill hopefully get inspired to add it all to MP later so stay tuned.

This whole "Lower Falls" area, as Im calling it, is simply the grouping of boulders lower than the main falls. Its actually just west of the steepest part of the south cliffs and starts where there is a 'beach' like area and continues till a more or less pond looking place starts.
A hand jam is nice but this is so easy you probably don't need eyeballs. Start as for "Smorgasbord" but just go left through the big crack.

Pretty nice especially if wanting a nice easy first course before trying something heavy and greasy. Could probably top out a lot of places but just followed it until it felt most pure. 

Ella and Lillian made the hike out with us and kept chel company on the nice little beach.

On the right side of Simple Crack, there is a hold you can start on. You can climb up from there.

Edit 03/09/2020 - I saw this route added on Mountain Project as a traverse into what I had called "Pit Stop".

This is the furthest west climb on the north side. Literally on the bottom pond level this climb starts in compression off of a small rock that is sticking a bit out of the water. When you squat start, you will know you started correctly if you ass is gently caressed by the sweet lapping of dirty city run off.

Cool squeeze feature and pretty cool compression moves but its quite short. Probably should have flashed but spent 11+ burns falling on the last move of "All washed up", Can someone please teach my sweat glands to take a chill pill? This is getting ridiculous.

Did the direct version to get a bit more climbing in before calling it a day. And what a day it was!! Oh no, not for climbing, I did terrible at that, but today was Chelsea's first day at Joshua Tree!! 

I think it is pretty surprising to see JTree for the first time. It is always magnificent to see the fields of Joshua Trees and endless piles of granite. Even if I know its really just piles of choss, they are still beautiful. 

Stars are always good too. Oh and sunset. Yes. What a day it was!
Felt dumb, forced, contrived, un-intuitive, silly. Really an all around stinker when it comes to climbing. This poo poo pile is the traverse to the left of Dream Sequence
Directly opposite All Washed Up, helped me get All Warmed Up.

Chaseypoo is my man. He drove all the way from bishop just to see me. Well either see me, or do these sweet sweet bounders. 

Great Sunday with buddies, beers and amazing vegan enchiladas from my love. So fun to finally show someone sandy my new local crag. I think Estate Tax Project and "Fly you Fools" Project will go next time if friction is good!

Chaseypoo snagged this FA, but I will get Estate Tax so woot woot for me. A great warm up boulder overall, and we found a very contrived line that is going to be virtually impossible to describe. Start to the right of Face Climb, and to the left of Face Climb Center and basically skip all the good holds. Good feet from a right hand gaston gets you to the "plate". Chase got the FA so he can name it and grade it if he wants.

Based on true events:
After their fight at the Bridge of Khazad-dûm, Gandalf and the Balrog both fell into the deep chasm. Gandalf was burned by the Balrog's fire on the way down, then almost froze in the water at the bottom. He pursued his foe for days through dark tunnels, and then all the way up the Endless Stair to the top of Durin's Tower in the living rock of Zirakzigil, where the two engaged in a two-day long battle at the pinnacle of the Silvertine above the clouds. They fought in a narrow space upon Celebdil, above the mists of the world
-The Lord of the Rings
Area epic my dudes! This is real climbing. Even though I'm pretty sure most falls would hit the landing, and most of those would not tumble past that, there is a very real non-zero chance that you fall a good 50 feet off the canyon wall and die. Located on the west corner of the "Where Eagles Dare Boulder" start standing on opposing jugs and work your way right through the overhang/arete feature.

On the south side of the river just west of the tallest part of the cliffs there is a boulder that you can crawl under. Start on the on a left-ish facing blocky hold and just move left out of the cave to the good shelf and top out. Draggy but it isn't the worst climb I've ever done.

I cant believe how many lines we have managed to squeek out of this little lemon! Wow-wee!! I think this clocks in as the 8th line on the Face Climb boulder. Start on the "Face Climb" ball hold and just dyno all the way to the top. Good fun. Lost a lot of thumb skin on the pre-send attempts.

The time is 4-5 day beers, as Scott and I discuss working, pursuing your passion, the end of the NFL and the baser instincts of human beans.

Because of the time my foot kept picking on the start, but as soon as I stuck the move out right off the greasy grimy chossy Toxic Avenger hold, it was smooth sailing.

A line that never should have existed. There just isn't any space between Rave and Last Dance! That being said I am all about contrivance as a means to stave off boredom or create new era movement. 

I think I did this in a new way which is kinda cool. Started as for Rave, then went right hand to the classic broken crimp with my right hand as a gaston. Threw a high left heel and locked that baby down. Crossed left hand up to a small previously un-chalked pocked crimp thing then jumped right to the last dance jugs. Felt harder than "Last Dance" and was pretty cool!

The time is definitely 5 day beers now. I see a bunch of people calling this V6. I don't like to be called not Marcellus Wallus, but damn this did not feel like what Chubbs said to do when putting in Happy Gilmore. Rather, I felt like Happy when that gory damn clown wont let my ball through. That being said once I switched to a hockey stick I could put like a pro. 

The holds on the lip as you make the hard moves left felt real bad. Quite fun tho.

A frosty little day beer to start your day!! MmmMMmM!!

Three cheers for my boys Scott and Nathaniel! A great weekend filled with day beers, night beers with a small spattering of climbing. Nate's Psyche Tank is pretty low at the moment (you better refill soon my dude) but Scott is still a certifiably crazy insane mofo.

Drove out the the Milks excited to try Soul Slinger but 6 inches of fresh pow pow stopped that quest in its tracks. Luckily I bought and brought chains. My sweet little Hocus Focus proved challenging to install the chains on and drew blood on both Scott and my forearms. The milks are just gorgeous blanked in fresh pow, and a slick icy road proves fantastic for crash pad sketching.  

Anyway, eventually got to the Happys and eventually got to this boulder. Time is irrelevant but it was about 3 or 4 day beers in. Drew and Kody always told me how bad this climb was but I rather enjoyed it. I had dope beta and the victory top out is quite nice.

"iWatch Boys!". A more inspiring sentence has never been said when sending this rig. 

News flash Scott hates the word "rig". No idea why. Maybe it makes him thing of those big oil rigs and pollution? Maybe he is afraid of semi-trucks. Who knows. What I do know is that this climb is legitness. Lets do Scotts new proposed star metric for climbs

[*] - Is the climb between 7 and 15 feet tall, with a good landing?
[*] - Are the holds solid?
[*] - Is the line pure?
[*] - Is the movement good?
[*] - Is it aesthetic?

The order of stars are important, don't forget that. Needless to say this is a good ass line. Thank you Scott for those metric. 

Also, soft. I could have sworn I remembered seeing this being V8 which shows that memory is always perfect. I used the sweet extend-O right heel hook, Scott did a sick knee bar. First climb I have done where i pinched a nerve or cut off blood flow or something because my ring finger was completely numb at the top.

Guys! Guys!! I did a thing! I used my body and got on top of a thing!! Hooray!

I cant believe this doesn't get even a single little blip of a fluttering heart in the book. Like I could see people getting severely hurt just climbing to the base of the climb itself! 

I think technically most falls would hit the landing, but with a landing significantly  smaller than those little yellow helicopter pads on the tramway towers, landing is not whats worrisome; its bouncing. Bouncing like a bumble all the way down the canyon; possible making the quickest descent to the parking lot possible. At least there is an upside.

Anyway, surprisingly this was my third session over 10 years on this RIG. It came down to one mega trust of a right hand jam to get my left foot up, otherwise it was cake. I will go back with my boy big Scott one of these days because he can and should do it. 

The fact that you can see this line from the parking lot and its inspiring as hell, I am willing to continue my recommend whoring.
Just to touch this boulder as much a possible. Start far right side with a little combustion and slap once or twice to some downpulling that may prove confusing to the tired lad.

Another area test piece. RPC is shaping up to be quite a nice little San Diego gem of an area. I mean the Whole "PoGo" boulder is gonna blow up with variations I just know it. I can see at least two back side jonses and thats before 5 o clock on a Saturday! Start standing with right hand on the obvious jug and chose your grip, standard, western, or spock. I chose spock which was a little weird at first but then suddenly it just felt right. Left hand on an opposing jug. Work up straight through the sloper depressing using subtle combustion. Very inspiring line.

After getting the biggest split of my life attempting Estate Tax, I thought my day was for naught. But I saddled my metaphorical horse one more time and figured I'd try some of the other stuff I had scoped. Boy I was pleasantly surprised. Everything I got on today was super fun with enjoyable movement! Even this dumpity dump dump got my psyched! 

I did the obvious one move stand start a few weeks back and figured I'd look for a lower start. I found one! That one broke, burned down and then sank into the swamp. Just kidding! it just was transmorglified and then shattered into a million pieces. Just kidding again. But seriously the first set of holds I tried to start from shattered. But it meant I had to start slightly lower on slighly stronger holds and those stayed up. Started with double heel toe cams in on the pretty steep (albiet tiny) roof. Make a hard move to the obvious block start of "Garbage Compactor" stand.

Sometimes you find amazing things: this is a beautiful bullet rock with crazy patterns. Kind of a shame the roof doesnt have any holds but that sets up a nice desperate throw from river polished slopers on the lip to the top. Starts on a detached part of the boulder and after sticking in a totally mandatory but not needed knee bar, set up on the best part of the slick lip and jump up and left to the good juggy arete. A little harder since the landing really isnt that good, but its not very high so I think youll pull through. I bet the straight campus from the slopers goes, but it might be V9 alone.
As obvious as they come and as such I have an innate sense of direction. ok. where am i? Oh yeah no way is this an FA but a must do little guy.
Start right hand in the super obvious pocked and left hand on the spock jug. A hard move leads to easier climbing. Here is your order Jean Luc!

Now since bouldering isnt contrived enough on its own I figured Id take a Climb called "Garbage Compactor Sit", eliminate the largest hold on the climb wrap it in tin foil and give it to the queen as earings. Instead of moving out left to the big shelf, do a big lock off straight up to a cool pinch.

Start pretty much center of the face with right hand on a flat ledge and left on a lower crimp. Place right foot on then pull a hard foot move to get your left foot on the spock jug ive mentioned a few times. Proceed to do a rhetorical lock off and top out.
EDIT: Downgraded to V4 for consensus. I was tired that day so not surprised.

This climb probably shouldnt exist but i really wanted to touch that 24 karat hold. Seriously this hold is to die for. If you brought your silicon molding kit and sold copies of it id bet you woudl make a killing. Too bad its not usable in any real climb. le sigh. Start compressing the arete to the right of "Lower Falls Crack". Left hand on the compressing side of the crack.
ascents.zlaggableName: Why does she even have that lever?

ascents.comment: Now, based on a centuries-old translation of Norse texts, historians had believed that my name is the [Grecian] God, but after comparing the text to the ruins of a Viking shield, it was  found that one of the letters had been mistranslated. So, by changing this letter, and inserting the correct one, we find that "The [Grecian] God of Shittiness and Modesty but only one of those is True", the key and Classic Snadbox member, is not [Grecian] at all, gentlemen, but [GREASIN]! (softly) Pause for effect. Gentlemen, I’ll take your questions now.

Today my friends finally discovered my deep, deep, dark secret: that my true name is the Greasin God.  Not a very good problem but, not a good name for that matter, I like points give me all the points! 

Would have been flash but apparently it doesnt start on teh obvious place... it starts around the corner... lower and deeper... and worse.
That left hand is just so bad! Well, obviously not because you just locked it off to grab a non-existent hold.
Mantle Classes are in session everyone! Waffleman you fail. LIB you also fail. But when you bloom, you will be the most beautiful mantelers of all!
A Golden Winged Warbler, thats another one for exotic Red Rocks Dyno Bingo! Not too far but top is not a jug. Enjoyable!
Not bad actually. Plus the name is all time. Hard to do with a beer in each hand... hard enough so that I had to put one beer in my pocket.

(pearl boulder): AK has caught the climb anything bug!! Hell yeah my dude. Too many people don't even enjoy climbing anymore. I'm a total hipster because I climb to climb my dudes. Think about it. The points are nice too.

Have you ever had one of those days where you feel downright terrible, yet somehow since your expectations are so low, you end up actually climbing super well? Yeah I was so smart that I preemptively assumed that my sleep deprivation, head ache and body fatigue would create such low expectations that I would be guaranteed to crush. Mamma we made it!
Six Pack!? More like 24 pack! And even that wont be enough for these Sandy Bois and Gals.
#WhatsYourCactusStatus
Yes! Finally a climb I can get behind!

Even with a devastated temple of a body, I apparently can still hurl myself at things. Thank you dynos for salvaging a otherwise dismal showing. This is a very rad looking feature on the boulder behind Mr. Moran. Decent holds with terrible feet and a bad landing. Shoutout scott for the sick angle, and shoutout Pickle Rick Tank for being green and allowing me to wear him  backwards.  That green contrast was quite necessary to compliment the all to white whiteness of this Grecian God Bod. Why did they have to carve me out of marble!

Looking at this climb it is impossible to believe I have not done it. I mean it looks exactly like a climb I would do. All my friends even said: "David, this looks like a climb you would do". Despite that 8adotnu says I havent, and I log literally everything (thank you my loyal watchers for your continued patronage), so I am inclined to believe I havent. Maybe i got so wrecked being a weak little boy on Monkey Bar Direct all those years ago and I simply couldn't do it? Makes you think. Anyway, whether or not I have done this is of utmost importance because these 5 VPoints are the deciding points as to whether or not I beat the birthday boy on his birthday. I did it in cruisers dabbing all over the place but I did it and im cashing in these points.
(By Spitting Venom): Also not bad. I couldn't even tickle my pickle today while wearing a pickle. Talk about failing at life.
(By Spitting Venom): honestly not bad. These are some hard earned VPoints.
Almost too drunj at this point, I was about to try this barefoot... glad I was dissuaded by chaseypoo.
Dark with no light. First time I have ever had to find feet holds with my hands. Thats how you know this is mega soft.
I guess the pun is because you use your foot? A little weak I must say. Pretty excited to extend this by 2 moves and gain 7 VPoints.
Alright if the last climb was a weak pun this is even weaker. Come of First Ascensionists! With great power comes great responsibility! Not a bad face climb tho.

Our boy Zach doing us up at the Yard House. Shout out you. I gave you the best review you will ever get, and a bomb ass tip. I dont remember exactly what it said since i was drunj... but i think i called you my pimp. I hope your manager likes that.  

Tried this no pads in cruisers and blew the flash. Grabbed shoes but still no pad and wish I had because its a toughie.
(By Spitting Venom): Red Rocks is clever. I hate unnamed climbs but this "left", "right" "center", "arete right" nonsense has me taking crazy pills.
So soft it took more burns that Dirty Rail. Tried the extension from Dirty Rail 3 times and at 20ish moves a pop I became wacky wavy wobbly inflatable tube man. Number one goal to get back on!
I am very curious how to officially pronounce this. So afraid I would not flash but then I realized its ridiculously enjoyable and climbed the good climb.

Who know what the saying "Pearls before Swine" means? All I know is that I can't do Pearl Necklace... and all the shade is well deserved. Lukily I can find some solace in the fact that fat fingered Gabe qualified my suckiness saying it all depends on how you hold the pocket! See guys its

(By Spitting Venom): The hardest VPoint of the trip. This boulder is a pretty dope warm up. Maybe next time I am not desecrated by the undone "Dirty Slut" I will warm up here and then try that soft thing over there by Born Under Punches.

Chaseypoo you scored an Insanely Dope Hotel room! Thank you for letting me and LIB sleep showered with you at this pristine Not Red Rock Facing, but really Red Rock Facing, must call to reserve the pool, heinously red entry doors, hotel. Your mommy knows how to show her boy a Happy Happy B-Day. Next time I will bring more beer and I promise I will get in a hot tub and marinate with you.

Oh the climb? Rubbish. Cool start just but sandiest heel of all time and just not good.

Hey watchers? Remember when i forgot how to climb on that dyno attempt on "Pearl Necklace"? Good times. No video but I'm sure the memory is forever immortalized. 

First move is a little weird but overall decent climb. Will likely do again.

(Jones'n Start): Silly intro to the same Awesome climb. This climb is even better by the fact that you could get 15 points just by doing all the variations. Too bad I am way too tired to do the V6 Variation. 

Missed the pads on a pre send burn, but my boy AK stepped up with some serious spotting game.
(Stand): Awesome climb. One big more from comfortable crimp to big ol comfortable hold, all topped with a nice mantle lesson.

(On Mr. Smiley): The walk here was miserable in a work out shell of a body. The running theory is we were all poisoned and are currently suffering the consequences.

Oh the climb? Actually pretty good. Starting compression feature is cool.
(On Mr. Smiley): Not unnamed.... Hah! you cant fool me red rocks guide!
(On The Alexisizer): V1 probably.
Still squeaking points out of this boulder. Might warm up here in the future. Cant believe there were three generations of UCLA climbers at this boulder today. So cool. #WorstGeneration

This climb will be my ode to my friends. Happy Birthday Shirley, you are a man amongst men and I love you dearly. Now we will be the same age for a good 3 month. Good work on those poems. My jelly beans can always be yours. Camaraderie with my dudes is always a blast. I miss you all. AK nice job having enough energy and finger durability to send this glorious feature, thanks for picking be up at Chelseas Grandparents and sharing a glorious 2 for 3 with me at that special place. Drew great to finally meet Jamie and always a pleasure to feel your Butchoosole, Booka Booka Booka you you you strong strong strong boi boi boi. Marina I am always insanely impressed, sorry chase doesn't know how to tell where climbs start and so jealous and inspired by your bloody bloody tip oozing its way up the ultra classic pearl necklace. Scott you are my baby boo. Please let me hold you.
Very cool looking rock, good climb, but not amazing. Racking up my stars for the day... now as long as someone doesn't land on the god awful Boo tile.
Sometimes I amaze myself.

From my driveway to the boulders was 25 minutes. A 14 minute drive and 11 minute jog (with a soft J). I've been making goose egg trips out to RPC, desperately trying to finish up "Estate Tax" before it gets swooped by another strong-strong boi. 

I actually came out on Friday as well (one aforementioned of those goose egg performances) and broke my favorite hold off of "Estate Tax"! I was a sad-sad boi that day. I was so sure it would go down... and i guess it did, but not in the way I wanted. Anyway, don't worry my dear-dear bois, the project still goes but now slightly more contrived and slightly harder. Probably solid V9 now. 

That all being said its Poison Oak season everyone! Be careful! I trimmed a bunch on Friday (and my poor sister Eileen somehow got the devils itch on her forearm). I also moved a bunch or rocks from the landing to cover up a lot of that poison oak and after lowering the landing by maybe 6 inches a lower start to "The Penthouse" felt quite natural. 

So to prevent another my poor body from having to lay another goose egg I sent this one move extension of "The Penthouse". It was a very soft V7 before so maybe now its solid for the grade? Start with the cool right hand pinch thing and any lower left hand.

PN (Proposed Name): This is usually just referred to as "The right arete of Italian arrogance". Sit start with left hand on the low under cling and right hand up pinching the arete. Some slaps and tension lead to better holds (the ones you start "American Ignorance" on), from which you can pull directly up using a black xeno. Glad to find beta that was not Drews original beta. 

Shoutout Drew for beeing a baller (apparently he is scared of bees now). After climbing a full day at Woodson, when all the weenies bailed, drew ran out with me to RPC to slay some area classics and take down the "Tax Evasion" project. I wonder what clever terrible name he is cooking up. Thank you for intentionally not sending the "Estate Tax", I am pretty sure you could have finished it and for that you have my thanks.
