PRNF: This is in all likelihood not an FA but if no one corrects me ill take it. 

I wanna shout out my Valley Bois: Chase and Kody. I don't mean 'Valley' as in they enjoy Yosemite (or Mineral King, which they do). I mean it as in if you were to plot their psyche and climbing ability as a time series they would be in a serious dip. 

Kody I was very happy to climb with you at Woodson. I really hope you come back and share some more beers with me. I also really hope when that time comes you will slap up that rightward sloping chodler with me. I know you will have a good time. Also RPC is just waiting for you... as am I. 

Back to the climb: This thing stand starts on the juggiest part of the right arete of the Italian arrogance boulder. Traverse left through the slight shelf and join the top of the standard Italian Arrogance. Pretty cool movement actually. Cant wait to do the sit of "America" into this which drew said he will name "America F*** Yeah" which I really hope he does, because its an awesome name.
Not bad it you ignore the top out choss. Fun balancy arete. Started both hands on the slopers and did one move to the arete.

Soft once you find the beta. Took C. Hoss a surprisingly long time since he should have felt right at home with those loose granite grains. Also surprisingly enjoyable since I never heard of this before.
The only better name could have been dishy choss. While the dishes seem to have cleared up choss wise, the top out is a rainstorm of choss. Felt rather hard. Third send train with my long lost boi.

Wow. This climb is all time. Everyone walks by it without a second glance despite many aesthetic qualities. Erik was struggle bussing so figured I would give him inspiration by doing it in my flip-flops. If anyone can actually do this as their first V3 ill buy them a 6-pack of any beer they choose*** ***Not redeemable for cash. $30.00 maximum value

More like 'Soft Grit' am I right? If you are a squeeze boi like me this is your steeze. A very cruxy first right heel on like nothing. Quite enjoyable. I never tried this stuff becuase Hero Roof / Iron Man area is always so crowded. Corona and high winds helped clear the milks out making it prime for the sandbox to swoop in and reminisce.

So should have flashed, but used wrong foot at crux. Cant really decide if I like this problem overall or not but i loved one move. After exiting the roof I end up with left hand on a shitty minipinch and a good left foot and needing to bump the right hand. What makes this great is the hold I bump to is about an inch away from my face. Pretty funny to seem so close but still be far! If only I had fingers on my face (as long as they were washed)
Didn't realize the V8 was a jump start so we all did the cheater version. Rather enjoyable climbing. We probably had perfect conditions. Another one I am surprised rarely gets done.

Every time I told someone I had not done this they responded with 'Wow! I cant believe YOU haven't done that soft piece' (shoutout Jenny, Scott, et al.). They were all absolutely right, but this was a serious epic for me! Too much delicateness and balance for this brute. Soul Slinger has been on my mind even since Chase popped his V9 cherry on it (or maybe ever since Key-Lime started projecting it), but I failed session after session. My last 3 times to bishop, the Milks were snowed out, so I was relieved to finally get a rare opportunity Morty. High wind was pretty optimal for maximizing friction with hands as wet as mine. Great to knock you nemisis out early in the trip that way you can start drinking beer earlier... although pretty sure I was already a beer or two deep at this point. Nice work Erik on the quick send yourself! 
	
Really amazing how impossible this thing originally felt and how easy it feels when dialed. Truly an great rock climb!

Somehow I managed to avoid the glory jug out right and just slither up on the slopers. Maybe I didnt even do "Soul Slinger Right", maybe I did "Soul Slinger Slightly Right". Always looked harder than the standard line but once you start putting in the burns it unlocks. First send train of the day with my long lost boi

Sandbox took this beauty out for the best date of her life. Started with a casual walk on the beach, a homecooked meal at sunset and a shared bottle of Pinot Noir snuggled near the fire with the soothing pitter patter of rain outside. Translation: we gangbanged this rig. 
	
	I had never seen anyone working this but its gets 2 stars in the book so figured I'd try. Shortly after we had almost 10 Sand men + women at the top. Fun sequences with intersting holds and movement. Awesome to see the beta change over burns and hone in on the 'softest' optimal sequence. 
	
	Always a pleasure to be objectified and used for your body.
This wall is pretty fun. Tiring myself out on the several slightly arbitrary variations.
I think Natebro is getting stronger than he realizes. Certaintly a softie this one, but could still be V8? More importantly 7B is not a grade.
Lives up to the hype! Glad this thing is getting more attention lately because it deserves it! Cool holds and awesome sequences. JQuee making the send of the day on this.
Hardest problem for me this trip. Probably just too devastated. But it took seeing a 4-tips-not-bleeding Shirley sending to inspire me enough to send.

Now is the time for David Vasko's long diary entry:
	
	This trip was the reunion of 13 longtime UCLA friends spanning the Sandbox and outlying areas: Pictured from left to right in the only group picture taken: Erik, Ari, Jacquie, Kelsey, Drew, Chase, Micro, Jenny, Gregor, Nate, Akhil, Jessa and Tomasso. It was the worst of times, it was also the best of times. Amazing to see everyone but I wish it wasn't under the doom and gloom that is Corona. Many of these friends I have not seen in years and despite all that time and distance our reunion was timeless. Literally felt like we had all just walked out of 529 1/2 on our way to pizza after a session of climbing in John Wooden. Unreal. Everyone looks exactly the same, I wonder who will get fat first. 
	
	Classic warm up on sunshine boulder with no pads, classic day beers 'mmMmMM!', classic butt touching (sPOTDing), classic bleeding fingers, classic crash pad island, not so classic house to crash in, neo-classic dinner at the Rambler, not at all classic at all lack of hackey sack, classic douchbaggery from the sandboxes biggest douchbags, classic asshole-ery from your biggest assholes, classic Erik still being a strong-strong boi, classic sandbox tanks, and more classic and non-classic items. 
	
	On my way to Bishop from San Diego I stopped in Upland to drop off my girlfriend. As I get out of my car there is an audible hissing noise which was soon determined to be my front left tire loosing air at an alarming rate. So I take it into the shop and they tell me its a miracle none of my other tires had popped. I proceeded to replace all 4, which was perfectly timed to pick up chase at 5pm. I wonder if I shoudl still be amazed that my life works out so well. If it hadn't started hissing then i bet it would have popped way out in the table lands.
	
	I was also riddled with poison oak which was not so sick. Glad the asshole fears turned out to be just fears... itchy fears... 
	
	Now place your bets in this Corona Pool! Winner take all!
Rather hard for 5, but super rad big move.

Second Ascent. Surprise send this one. Was literally warming up on the moves while I waited for non-existent clouds to give me better temps on "Estate Tax". No expectation of sending at all. I thought this was harder than "Estate Tax" but that obviously wasn't true. I also thoughr this was probably V10 but that also obviously wasn't true. Start move felt okay so I gave it a ground go and held on. I think perfect heel hook and toe hook beta makes cruxes easier. 

Came out to RPC today despite my better judgement, regarding the pandemic. Had not left my house since last Sunday night, and almost didn't go today but I was afraid Drew would cruise "Estate Tax" and I want the V10FA points, I really do Brian. I was honestly afraid someone would chastise me for breaking Corona Isolation at RPC but instead I saw swarms of people (and a rattlesnake). Like seriously there were more people than a normal Saturday. I even saw an extremely nice ranger (or wild life volunteer) and instead of warning me about Corona they warned me to be gentle to the wildlife. Oh that and watch out for poison oak, at which I showed them my ravaged arms which are riddled with it. No one was 6 feet apart. It's like no one is worried. Sigh. I hope this pandemic doesn't get too bad here in Cali. Wash you hands and don't touch your face.

Wanted to see how hard breaking "Estate Tax" would be by going from the "Penthouse" jug right into "Estate Tax". Started left hand in the good right facing jug you cross to on "The Penthouse" and right hand in a slightly smaller right facing jug just below. Pull yourself on and make a few slightly extended gaston moves to get into the top out of "Estate Tax Project". 

Kinda fun but this climb will most certainly and seriously decrease the life span of that already hollow jug flake. Might make a cool Extension to "The Penthouse" or "Tax Evasion".

Harder than I expected without using the better more friable jugs. And way more hard coming into this from "The Penthouse": when you come in from "The Penthouse" your right hand is in the better part and matching is real tough and gross. Making "The Penthouse" cross into the worse part of the jug would be real difficulty... may have to think on this extension.
ascents.zlaggableName: Well, it's not a pry bar

ascents.comment:
I've been making weekly trips out to RPC trying to send "Estate Tax", but the project is still open. Next week for sure!

I have been loving biking to the boulder from my house which takes about 30 minutes to get to the boulder (5.5 miles), and about 35 minutes home. I bike with my big organic pad so I'm sure I look pretty rad! 

This climb is in the narrow corridor between Mr. Longarm and The Penthouse. Insanely difficult to not dab, and feet are pretty poopy.  Might be soft, I felt terrible.

In the wash from the circa 2016 mudslide, in the same area where the hills sing, this is down the creek about 50ft on the left side of the creek. Start on the right side of the boulder on a ledge and move left through some big features. Butterflies like the water section. Chelsea likes butterflies. A kaleidoscope is a group of butterflies.

First FA for bounders 6! Likely not an actually FA but i will be the first to log it on 8a. On the Timber gap trail, when you hit the flat open meadow-ish section before you hit the wooded part of the gap, the hills just sing. You will know you are there because of the singing. My father calls this section of the trail "The Sound of Music" and this FA is an ode to that. Start on the West side of the boulder with both hands on a large ledge. Mantle up onto the ledge the finish up.

Start in the glorious crack feet toe hooking on the prow and follow the obvious crack all the way up. Good aesthetic climbing and an unbelievable view make this climb quite special. Just off the right side of the Franklin lake trail as you start to ascend from the first lake.

A chossy piece of rock sits atop an even more chossy rock basically lacking corperial form and might better described as roughlt stacked sand. Anyway, on this rock you find this glorious climb. Not too far off the trail, adn would be decent but its poor rock quality leaves somethign to be desired. Start on left side

Actually looked at this years ago with Chase, Drew and Nathaniel but tired eyes and dry psyche blurred our "line" vision. Immaculate rock quality, with good body tension and an irresistable back flag make this climb quite good. After sending this I had enough psyche to propel me up FLorence peak (20.5 total miles)! I gained enough ground on the final switchbacks to the pass, that I figured I had time to test the scramble. Quite fun, and another peak in the valley checked!

A direct finish to Biggorron's Sword. After a move or two, dyno straight up to the lip and mantle away. Insane glory awaits. Dont forget to place that bomb on that off colored section of wall when you hear the tell tale chich-chich-chcih

Left side of the Crumbs Roof Boulder. Start matched on undercling and go up through jugs. Awesome job Daniel and Jenny! Will not forget Jenny showing up for this hike with literally nothing but the clothes on her back! 17.5 miles! woot woot!

A surprisingly fun line on this crumble pile of a boulder. Start in the center-right of the crumbling feature and move right from the crumbling feet to cool crimps and ultimately a tough rock over to better top out. Trying to blitzkrieg some climbs while we wait for our hiker gang to re-group!

I actually did this one almost a decade ago but never filmed it so it never happened. This one starts on the south end of the boulder that the Alpine Chalet (now called Paradise Ridge) sits. Start both hands on the obvious ledge and find a way to mantle up

Same start but eliminate all holds to left and do a big thrutch right to the slopers on the overhanging lip. Match up and mantle up moving right to make mantle easier. You have now discovered secert passage to the Alpine (now Paradise Ridge) Chalet! Way to go!

On the creek side of the Alpine Chalet, there is a cool rock with a small overhanging lip. Literally 20ft to the left when looking at the firepit. Start on the obvious pinch edge  directly below the overhang and move left ultimately to grab a jug sidepull. As a bounus grab some of the discarded half burnt logs to help your fire!
Same start as Chimney Sweep but go straight up mantling on the overhang. Thank you Chel for the great footage and support! Thank you Ripple!

Short but felt very hard last season. Feels short for a climb, but hey, the start hold is cool. Thank you Chel for the support! Shout out some of the amazing hikes we did! Timber gap + first peak, Nature trail with the cool cave excursion, and Paradise Ridge to Sootoro's Tree Bridge!
Go on, spoon it.
A low start to the ultra classic "The Monarch". Certaintly adds some pump as well as some slip-n-slide potential. Sandbox, get out here!

Surprisingly hard for a one move wonder. If you can crimp better than me this may feel like piss but ive been tryingt his thing since 2010 so must be soft. I wonder who else instantly realized there is a comment length limit....
Shout out Eileen and Daniel for making it up to Sawtooth Peak for their first time!! Summit Cuvee baby!! Michael im sorry about the heebeegeebees.

I would say 4 pads is the bare minimum. I scrambled up the talus field with 4 Pads (3 big and a metolius), and it was rather tiring. This feels surprisingly exposed as soon as you pull on, and a few slaps certainty get the heart rate going. Probably closer to V5 but that gets the scare and pad carrying grade. Squeezing in some early morning climbing to make the most of my last day in paradise!

This climb would be a test piece anywhere. I think a low start goes too! Thank you whoever told me to ducktape my knee pad to my leg. Made the knee bar SOO much better. Thought it was feeling closer to V9 then I did it fresher and m-flashed it twice. Soft. Kinda wish I was the one to FA this... stupid, big, strong drewbie.

A link up of "The Penthouse Low" into "Well, its not a pry bar". Is probably V8, but it took me a surprising amount of sessions. I think an easier sequence could lock it in at V8, so i reserve the right to downgrade when it sees some action. Its contrived as hell, all good holds past "the penthouse" jug are off, which forces a hard match to start "Well its not a pry bar". Estate Tax next trip i swear!
Cant believe I never tried this before. Maybe the pit is new? I love dang it holes so hard to imagine I wouldn't immediately hop in. A cool power move or 2 leads to class 4 hiking.
Good features on a cool corner of a block. Someone did a lot of work to clear the poison oak away from this climb and while they may not be the hero we deserve, they are the hero we need.
More easy slabs in RPC. Finally a day where there are not many people out, to try these newer lines. RPC getting more traffic these days!
I did the stand a while ago but I did not have the vision for this extension. Adds a surprising amount of good climbing to the line I originally saw. Cool use of an undercling.
Always thought it looked to easy to be considered a climb... but someone else did it, so i did it. Enjoyable enough!
A hard pull off the ground, leads to some enjoyable arete moves. Go up and left keeping left hand on the face and right hand on the arete.

Fun move to the lip with a good top out. Cant believe I hadnt cleaned this boulder yet! Seriously as convenient as it gets, right in Cold Springs Campground with probably about 5 lines of V8+. Going to be a slaying when the Sandbox finally joins me for a beer out here.
Better than I expected! Eileen found this rock for me and it is named in honor of the lovely ladies who made this night so memorable!

Start on the lowest plate of the small boulder below the "Shipwreck boudler". Pretty silly since there are jugs just above where you start but starting there forces either a hard campus or an enjoyable toehook sequence on the arete.
Really a piece of crap, and actually two boulders.... you start.. mantle on teh firs one.. then mantle the next one.... climbing through a brush the whole time...

Interesting. Cool start hold and really cool mantle shelf at the end (about 15 feet up!). For the crux move I had to do some weird pointer middle finger psuedo-pocket in the crack and rock over a heel using that. I'm sure there is an easier way but damn that crack bites!

Almost a good climb. Unfortunately the right side is quire shattered and every hold feels hollow even though some are quire large. I wander if there are so Rupees in side? maybe a heart at the least..
Some of you may die, but its a sacrifice im willing to make.

Im all about contrivancy these days. Pretty much tapped out RPC but still a few lines here and there. This boulder is funny because its super obvious when standing ontop of MR. Longarm but when you cross teh creek to go look for it, it suddently dissapears lol. Sit start on a very sharp crack and go up, skipping the huge start hold of "Be wary like gary".
One Ball, Corner Pocket : Start the same but bust left and up to the big sloper ledge and top out on teh sloper ledge using a key ball like hold up and left.

Same start as "Pit your Wits" but instead of going up and left, or even straight up, off route the huge jugs above and do a hard sequence due right.

Eking as much out of RPC as 3 dimensions of spaces allows
I had no idea this boudler even existed. Easy little scamper a hand to fist sized crack.

Also easier than Crimp Ladder.

Climb looks cool but lacks majesty, you know? Wish I would have flashed but it took me one burn to find which holds don't exist. Did it again first go two days later to rub it in Kodys face how easy it is.

Cheers my dude!

First time climbing on things I haven't personally FA'ed, and first time climbing not alone since mid-march. 

This climb is awkward.

Way easier than Crimp Ladder.

Probably should have tried this thing first since it turned out to be the easiest apple in the bunch. Coulda flashed!

Easier than Crimp Ladder

Chase would definitely agree.

Thank you Chase for inviting me outside. Unbelievable nice to see you and Kody. 

Remember touching this maybe 7 to 10 years ago and thinking it was gross and would never do it. Turns out both those thoughts were wrong. Some holds are a little odd but climb is fun. 

Hopefully next time I can wrangle that second dragon!

Also easier than crimp ladder.

Took a few group burns to find the beta then it went down like a 6 pack of double nut. So smooth and so delicious.

Also easier than crimp ladder.

Break ups suck, but at least this feature is amazing.

This thing has some inspiring holds. So many beautiful flat ledges that I just had to touch. It is a traverse so, i'm afraid it may have a tough life. Poor climb, be nice if you can. 

We also ended up making today's adventure even more fun by scoping "Natalie". Steep hikes, skipping rocks and marsh crossing were some of the highlights here. We had an almost 12 hour day out at way! So much adventuring!

What an adventure!! Not the climb (that, while cool was rather simple) The adventure I am talking about is the scamper Kody, Chase and I did all about the Talus! We were looking for Avada Kadavera so we proceed to spend at least 1.5 hours going all the way up through upper talus, back down, back up, around and through, all the way to grandmothers house. When we were about to give up we dropped all our pads and fanned out. After about 30 minutes we realized we were 5 feet away it looked dumb.
Incredible. We all ran it as the glory lap after crushing Hose Monster. Proudly makes the cut for Best V0's of California!!

Wish you all could have been there to watch the Fantastic Shirley Show. The amount of times that man threw himself at Meadow Roof was simple INSPIRING! Wow! Emmy deserving 

Was pretty destroyed but figured id flail on Crimp Ladder one last time in case the unthinkable and I sent. I didn't, but i did increase days climbed metric. 

Hiking all around with my double Big Organic and sufficient beer certainty tired me this weekend. Fitness baby! Now to fit some double nut browns into my mouth hole!

This thing is nuttier than pecan pie. Aesthetics are busting out the hull, movement is prettier than a mermaid figure head, and scare factor is "You best start believing in ghost stories miss Turner, yer in one!"

Tried this one 50-100 times over several years. Looks scary, but that last move is impossible to prepare for. Even with 8 large organics... still made 3 sad boys and 2 non-sad boys quiver in their boots. 

Thanks Kody for the "I think I had him" spot. Don't perish into the locker!

A few goes to test the big move beta. The fall is not bad, but high enough to require at steady head and some Miyazaki sized balls. I still haven't seen this movie.. I've been to scared... and now that I'm a sad boy I don't know if i could handle it. But if you fell... well maybe you might want to have brought the headstone. I hope no one dies in Grave of the Fireflies... or on it now.
Nice find Eileen!! If this thing was taller it would be incredible.! As it is its a short little guy, but fun! Mosquito 1.5 is shaping up nicely.

I told the boys this was V1 but after realizing it took me 4 tries, albiet without chalk and only cruizers... I decided they were right and gave it V2. Much more better.

This rock is few minutes after the Eagle-Mosquito split on the down hill side of a glorious look out rock. Surprisingly there is a small overhang with a huge fin that leads to an enjoyable dead point. 

Despite the moderately smoky conditions.. enjoy that Puff.. puff Panorama Boys!

Also this thing is too hard for Kody

nice #vision Scott! I wonder how long it will be before Ryan realizes you named a boulder after him... also wonder how much longer it will be until he does it? Man I would love Ryan to make it out to MK. Ill drink one to his memory. Cheers. Love that dude. 

This thing is so soft. Kody and Drew just flailing to make me feel better I guess.

I owe this FA to drew. It was a race and if anyone had scoped the top he would have bagged, but luckily no one did and he fell, which let me know to go right not left! Byah! 

I owe this name to Jamie! Although he spelled it "thiccq" which is just too outrageous. I liked the name though. Quite steep squeeze fest. Me likey.

What a beautiful block! movement is good too! Someone strong should try the V15 to the right.

A few things I cant believe. (1) Scott thought this was more natural to start one move in. Seriously!? God gives you a glorious pinch and you start one move in! As drew said "Yeah that definitely starts matched on the pinch". (2) Scott thought this was V8! Bah. He couldn't even do Ranger Cave! rofl. (3) How amazing this block is. It even has an incredible chilling cave.

Looks like its going to be trivially easy, but then it packs a punch. The starting angle is kinda tricky then the top is way more airy then you want after a 4 mile approach. Very aesthetic chunk of rock which just sings like a beautiful piano melody by Joe Hisashi.

The Igor Wall is incredible. Quality, Quantity and Proximity. Only negative is the top outs, but maybe when we rope it up we will find a more enjoyable top. This line doesn't care about that tho, since is Pure, like the Project. Rather frustrating! The final move is huge like her tracks of land.

Shout out Drew Chase Kody Scott and Eileen for joining me on another unforgettable trip to MK.  Thank you from the bottom of my heart, I hope you enjoyed it as much as i did. See yalls here next time!

I did this thing on my first day rope climbing outside over 10 years ago. Back then it was hard and I had to try and crimp feet. Today I m-flashed and actually crack climbed! Started the train with yer boy Zev. I guess I can confidently say I am slightly better. Incredible crack, that's all there is to say! Oh the downclimb is the crux for us boulderers.. reversing a crack is wack. First time for everything.

Left entrance. I know grades are hard to translate sometimes from Rope to Boulder... but this thing could and probably should be V7. We did it ground up and while I'm sure it would have felt a little easier with temps, this has a mono lock off and a dead point like to the lip like 20 feet high.

Regardless, simply incredible. Aesthetic, with great moves and even the mono is satisfying! Awesome weekend with my boy Zev! Sad MK fell through but it turned out pretty dope.

Scott asked me to reschedule our date to Wednesday that way he could that way he could save himself during our date and work out the following day at full strength in the gym. What a crazy man. Some people may have been offended, but Scott and I know each others bodies. He literally drove out to Mickeys just for some brief camaraderie, ambiance and stories of love. 

He also said "Im getting an appreciation for the coast. I don't like the beach or the ocean but its a great background". Legend.
Thank you for sharing a beautiful sunset with me Scott. I wish you the best of luck in all your endeavors: love, life and the pursuit or rock.

PRNF: If I am looking at Hitotsu this is the small face with crimps about 50 feet to your left. Fun enough, and it got Kristie stoked on climbing!! Her feet may be 5 sizes smaller than mine, but my climbing shoes worked just fine. No send for her, but shes hooked! Big Shout out to Kristie for letting me WFH at her house, and share an amazing week with more than copious amounts of wine! Handstands, coffee, Hamilton, smoothies, lost wallets, forgotten power cords. Amazing week!

Incredible line. Awesome features on beautiful looking arete... there might actual be TOO many features! Did the stand which was still a tad awkward to pull off the ground but overall this line is fantastic. Tahoe continues to Impress, this is my kind of bouldering. Thank you Scott and Drew for bringing me out.

My JAM! A little bit of squeezing followed by a very unique mantle!! Squeezing part is probably about V6, and the mantle alone is probably V7... but I am a Mantle Wizard so kind of hard to tell. Dialed the mantle in isolation after a few goes, then it took about 6 tries or so from the ground! Very stoked on this one especially because I didn't know it was a project at the time. Monkey saw a mantle, monkey had to do the mantle!
PRNF: Directly opposite Hitotsu - Will update name when guide comes out. One kind of off balance derp leads to easier top.

Surprised myself with this one! I didn't expect to be able to stick the first move so I played on the dyno once before trying from the ground. One left hand move then simpley dyno-ed to the jug which was AMAZEballs, but also most likely not V9. Tried going left and that was quite hard. BTW. Luna is just so gosh darn cute. Kristie winning the doggie bjorn lottery getting to carry that pup!

This is on your way to "Ashley to Classy" ( I now know its actually "Ashy to Classy" but my ear holes dont werk sometimes okay).  Its the boulder in the channel right before Ashy to Classy, big move from a large hollow-ish clake to a nice mantle lip encounter. Scott and I had a nice moment enjoying the top out together, sharing a laugh, and just absorbing each others company. ALSO drews new goggles wrecked his depth perception. Tall man hit ground harder than expected

PRNF: On the opposite side of "Ninja Warrior" climb from sitting through the face to the left of the tree. Good warm up-will update name when new guide comes. SCOTT being a wizard and just KNOWING that with this much sand, it was going to be a shit show. From staggered arrivals, to Chomering, to bushwacking, to carrying Cleo, to carrying Meredith, to Drew forgetting his climbing bag, to amazeballs sunsets, and having Kristie's FIRST bouldering experience be Echoland. Good ass time.

Simply Dusty, is there no other kind? Why flash gods why!? Show mercy! This was meant to me mine!! Egads, Zounds, other archaic curses!! Oh well, soft second go is clussic! Like dusty this climb is simply amazing. A tad reach but if you like squeezy and pretty boulders, have I got a song for you.  If you lived close enough, and climbed at my difficulty this boulder could basically be a home gym all on its own. GET ON IT.
Warm up for Amazing Gift I guess.

I high on that mantle hype YO. Scott told me he'd never seen anyone do this variation on Amazing Gift, so yeah I had to see, so I stood on my tippy toes and took a little peak, oh my god Becky look at that mantle. I found out that this actually isn't that hard and both Scott and (surprisingly Drew) followed suit. Quite nice.
RUSSLE WILSON TOUCHDOWN BEFORE THE HALF

Not sure if this is the correct climb. Chase said it was terrible but I thought it was rather good... which probably means its not correct. That or seeing Pinchy take a whipper from the top just made it all the more memorable. Dont worry folks he walked off the field of his own power and has no injury designation going into week 6. He even shoed back up before end of game and finished her up. Seriously though, pinhcy is a big boy. that was a lot of momentum.

Flash gods are cruel. Also drew is a big, big, mega big baby. I even have to hold his weewee as he peas. Oh that and hold a crash pad above my head so the sun doesnt hit him in the eyes when he tries a mega soft boulder. That gritty pinch makes this climb worth doing.
Minimal pad set up made that first move a tad scary. I trust my guys to both protect me from penetration, but also provide it. I know they know when each is appropriate.

North face of the "data and picard" boulder. Start right hand on an underclinggy pocket feature and left hand on an incut smallish crimp thing. One hard right hand slap leads to easy but slightly airy climbing to join Data and Picard. Kinda sad since there are a ton of cool pockety features but almost none of them are fully utalized.

I amaze myself by somehow finding even more contrived and or smaller,  and or dumber lines every time. So if you are looking at "Data and Picard" look left. Hop over the small channel and this boulder is directly in front of you. Yes its small, I'm AWARE. navigate around the left side which is in the creek. There is a series of left facing holds over the creek and just enough cheat stones to establish.  Pull a slightly scary "I don't want to get wet" move up and left to a good hold and top out.

Quite contrived, but good movement.  Start as for "Leisure Lagoon" but make a big move up and right to the obvious sloper. No, No, 
 no topping out yet, you must traverse right all way around the corner. Match up that sloper the use some great jugs on the corner to work around it and then top out on the side that faces due west.
ascents.zlaggableName: Sliding in on a Shrimp Sandwich

ascents.comment: On the boudler on the north side of data and picard, tha tone basically touching it but not, yeah its really little. Start on the right side and climb leftward using the arete. Eileen getting pumped on this rig! lol.

Surprisingly enjoyable. This boulder is on the north side of the Data and Picard boulder, almost touching it but not quite. Start on the left side of this boulder on two pretty good holds, and use the namesake out right to start.

Start "Tea, Earl Grey, Hot" but one move lower... thats why its HOTTTER. Just wait there is definitely going to be a HOTTEST. Left hand Gaston-ing the big spock side pull and right hand out right on the crimp on the face (the left hand for 'When I plucked the rose'.

When crossing the river to Data  and Picard, if you look to your left you might see this shit pile. No not because its bad (its not great), but because there was bird poop all over the start hold (not start hold). If you started there it would probably only be V1, but the climb is over water so to get to the start hold you have to downward traverse in from the left. Surprisingly the most interesting moves are the moves to get you to the "starting" blocky hold. Hard not to dab the water!

Contrivance to the max. Start almost as for "That tree is far away" but intentionally don't use the jug, and also off rout all jugs for the rest of the climb. Not bad movement really but when you gotta start putting tape on an outdoor problem so people can even understand.... its a little much. Oh and i literally got ants in my eyes on this one.

Shoutout Pichael for saving this GPS coordinate in his phone, 5 years ago and hilariously saving it as "A Nice Boulder". Would not have re found this without his coordinate. Great broken features on a 20+ foot tall boulder. This version juts up an left through the jug seam toward the channel. Its nice because if you climb V0 and get scared here you can bail into the channel, but for full value use the knobs to wrap around slightly and top out all the way!

A fun little Chimney right as a cluster of boulders starts! Always amazing to see split boulders like this and be able to see exactly how they used to fit together. Eileen tends to get claustrophobic but stepped up for this one! Also for the Diary portion, made Joel try a corner of this boulder that turned out to be free rock and fell spectacularly.

Awesome features: heucos in granite, and the pinch is to die for! Was not able to start matched on the under cling as I originally wanted, so had to start left hand already on the pinch. It might go from the low but the feet might be too bad. Its fern time of year so name is apt. Not a very tall boulder but the features make it worth. It all boils down to a pendulum move up and right.  Got dark quick, hanks Joel for bringing our only illumination.

An obvious "nose" feature behind the "Less is" climbs. A slightly awkward dabber rock to your left leads to a delicate arete/sloper crux to navigate the nose. Pretty sure any climb that looks like these nose features probably always ends up with some sort of nose reference or pun. Amazingly there is another very similar looking nose a few football fields up the ridge that I was not able to try due to time constraints. Kinda cool to have two so close!

This is a king line. The direct finish on "A Nice Boulder" through the amazing xenos and flakes. 20ish feet of amazeballs. Thank you All Might for your always inspiring presence and phrases.  So amazing to come full circle on this boulder after seeing it ~5 years ago and thinking "Wow that's cool but i will NEVER be back here", turns out I came back! Also good try on picking up that water bottle Eileen!
Cool features (some are a little too hollow to be great) on a vertical face lead to fun slopey top out. A stones throw from "Silver Lining".
A very easy crack I did on the more open ridge that Joel and Eileen were exploring. Did a handstand at the top.

Jamie's step father Robert making his presence known with this killer quote. As for the climb, tucked away an a channel between bigger boulders, start beneath and make one hard slap to the redeeming xeno features.
ascents.zlaggableName: I get it, I'd just rather go to bed

ascents.comment: Good Scoping Joel! I would not have even seen this. On the small boulder in front of "A nice boulder" there is a sequence of HUGE scoop jugs that climb naturally up the side.

Second boulder we stopped at on the Silver City Ridge adventure. This area starts a decent cluster of climbable boulders. This particular one is a small boulder that is actually a large flake of the one above it, you get to top out the flake and top out the subsequent boulder too. Eileen FA'ed the natural right exit, this version is explicitly on the flake using the small crimps.

This is one of those climbs where dyno-ing is actually easier than climbing. Like "Less is Less" start on the seam , only using features on the flake, but instead of crimping like Floop is mad, do a huge DP to the lip. Kinda cool! Also anyone know how to log a climb as First Go, but not flash since you did another climb that started in the same place?

Anyone else feeling rock deprived these days? Makes me feel thankful to still find untouched granite that I can call mine. An ode to all those people who can never get enough rock. This is the first rock we stopped at when heading up the ridge behind silver city, a kind of technical arete into a slopey top crux. Some really cool xenos and crack system on the death fall side, but not worth the risk way out here.

AMAZING slab crack! Super obvious and super good. Me Eileen and Joel running Train on this piece! My sister is a BADASS, she hasn't climbed in forever and easily sacks up for this kinda tall, slightly scary climb! Joes follows suit already giving this 3 ascents!! Very cool mid mantle into a pod, followed by some good crack feet or technical face smears. Can sit start for slightly more difficulty, but doesn't add any fun.

Rather good. A offset section of boulder creates a under cling feature all the way up! One "trust" issue move at the top but in general good feet all the way. Might be a dyno variation that would be rad... if i'm ever back here that is lololol.

On the backside of "The Garden of Elrond", start on an obvious left hand and a smaller crimp out right. Smear feet for a move to the lip then mantle. A ridiculous lie down start may be possible. This area is worth visiting for the beauty alone, climbing is secondary. Must do.

Careful Mr. Nazgul! If you are not careful you may fall into the torrent that is horses made of living water! A beautiful block that sports a odd hop start and a slightly worrisome mantle ensues. Picturesque!

The Waterfall is gorgeous. I have never been all the way down and this time of year when the water is low enough to expose the perfect river worn features, and allow closer inspection is fantastic. This obvious line starts ins a body sized river worn hole, next to a much larger feature which has water running year long. Its basically a cylinder hole. The climb is simply to start in that hole and mantle out! Way to go Eileen for doing this!

Tried desperately to force this line to start one hold lower, because as is its like an easy 1 move campus... this is the only climb done in the very disappointing talus field on the south side of the Kaweah river beneath the waterfall. IF i managed to do the hard start it would have added a wild slap and swing.. but oh well... will never be back here and as that homeless guy in Mr. Deeds says...

The beauty of this area is overwhelming. Especially now with fall colors add into the mix it humbles the mind. This climb is near the hacking grounds Me Eileen and Joel used. Start on a bad sloper and a tiny crimp rendered usable because of a great heel toe cam,  and either do a cool double gaston sequence, or power your way up to the better sloper. Good find Eileen!

Amazing boulder quite close to the Resort itself! How awesome. Name is a tribute to the amazing author Brandon Sanderson who continues to mystify my brain and transform my world. Seemingly bare rounded arete has just enough holds to make it amazing. to the left of "Ranger Rock" to the right of the burnt stump.

The kids call this boulder "Ranger Rock", so who am I to rob that from them? They are kids so they are obviously too weak to send this but I will honor them.  From Silver City head down the road with houses on the opposite side of the resort and take a right at the first fork. This will be on the left as you get to a grass clearing.

Start as for Data and Picard but make a cool left hand cross all the way to the pocket. From their finish up "Tea, Earl Grey, Hot", but uh oh! your hands are flipped!!! What ever will you do? First V8 at RPC lolol.
ascents.zlaggableName: Follow Every Toast with a Song

ascents.comment: The best part of this boulder is the crazy scoop features that you end up laying in to start it. A little moisture and you have a grade A slide! Physically not possible with a pad since there isn't room. On the west side of "The Cavern" area,there is a flat rail. Start there and go up and left desperately trying not to dab.

I thought this was going to be easier... i mean the jug is so close! But alas, because the ground is so close its hard to generate left. Had to use some smaller holds to allow a match before popping a back side jones to stick the ka-wham into the jug.

Start left hand same spot but start right hand about 2.5 feet lower and half a foot left of your left hand. Yeah its that subtle foot used for some other climbs. Rule #1, DONT use the big feature underneath the starting ledge for feet. I used some downward facing foot on the bottom of the ledge itselt, but the lower feature feels like basically the ground so why not just walk up. Cool shoulddery left lock off!
ascents.zlaggableName: When I Plucked the Rose Sit

ascents.comment: Another forced line that almost forces you to get wet. This thing is basically opposite Wet Cheeks, int the bottom pond. A fairly sit start hold exists and at least in summer there is enough dry rock under you to actually sit (just barely). A little awkward since there really isnt much space to move your ass, without getting wet.

Wow they force you to give # of attempts but the number doesn't go above 100! This was my project a the beginning of COVID and since then I have probably tried it around 200 times. I went about every week since March. Cloud 9 baby! Beer tastes good.  I also wish there was no comment length so I could go on a long Tirade. FAs are soft, everyone knows that. Come do it and downgrade, you wont! Was going to be the best V8 until the fin broke. Homer will tell tales of this. Not Mike, the Grecian one.

It was wet snow. . . . top holds felt quite oozy. . . so i instead went left hand to a right facing gaston, and then just popped right hand cross from the under cling to the top. Wonder if anyone else ahs done it that way. Chase was not happy because if i fell  during this insane move i would have crushed his son. His son was an immovable pile of gloom at the time.

Certainty soft but i think we hit a small window of perfect temps when we did the stand because the crux quickly started to feel harder and harder. I choose you, Pickachu Jesus! I mean if i have my choice that is.

Great rock climb with slightly odd first move. Thank you Chase and Marina for bringing me to Rock Creek for my first time! Wow! Not a huge area but some serious quality! Good temps quickly leading to "too good" of temps as snow flurries start to fall... stay tuned to find out if it was dry snow.... or wet snow! Dun! Dun! Duuuuuuun!

I started both hands on the face crimps... but even starting with left hand already up felt hard. Still waiting to find out if that was wet or dry snow... we'll tell you after this short message from our sponsor.

Honestly this looked way cooler that it felt. Don't get me wrong its definitely a great rock climb, but I just expectation bummed myself. This Bishop season teeing up to be quite the plushness. Very glad to be starting a paid subscription to climb V11 this season.

Post break. Quarantine skin is thin, so wasn't even gonna try but chase made it look soooo easy I just had to. Very nice lock off! Aftermath was only two sliced and bloody tips, but luckily, neither were mine!

Holy Gronk-amole! Thanks NFL newscaster for that beautiful pun on my STUD. Also this climb is confusing where to start and HARD. I started left hand on  the arete and right hand on an underling, and summoned all the strength inside me to get my ass of the ground, then magically move my right hand fast enough to catch the slopey lip and swing and also try desperately not to dab or fall off.  Had to run it back because of a micro-dab first send.
This felt so hard for me. Thanks Waffleman for reminding me that Super Froz is number 1 on my list. Its gonna go down like donkey kong!

The ending of this seems rather arbitrary. I got to the Hamtaro holds so i figure thats good enough. Mortal Combat next time baby!!! Im gonna go all Scorpion and rip the spine out if you know what i mean.
This V3 is the crux of the V7, in fact its the only "meat" of the climb if you will. Although I don't eat meat so maybe the "nuts" of the climb. That sound nice.
V7 in the new book and I'm taking it!! Good temps certainly help this, but that V3 top is quite the heart breaker. Glad I brought some nice frosty Double Nut Brown for your troubles!

Felt utterly impossible. Then i switched shoes, got bit by a radioactive spider, did a pec dance in front of a mirror and voila! I got some technique! I haven't been to the buttermilks in too long. These bullet patina holds are pavlovian.

With "Working Class" this boulder actually actually offers the bouldering world a decent set of climbs! Plus its close to the Bachar Problems, so its rather surprising these don't see more action. Small and interesting with crux top outs.
Smith you should be embarrassed having done it. But hey! Days climbed metric baby! Always a silver lining.

A little boulder walked into a bar and said, "Bartender, give me a cup of your finest Wiskey, on the rocks please!". The bartender  dusted off a fine bottle and asked "will this do?", the boulder said. "yessir". The bartender opened the bottle and poured poured it on the little bouders head and said "I love puns. Dont take life for granite. This ones one me.. well technically its on you ... but its on me"
Not bad. Not great, but I'm confident it wasn't bad. Awesome climbing with Old School Joshua Tree climber Ryan! Hope I get to climb with you again... maybe in Levy? Would love to see the Dojo!
Nothing like a nice soft V2 at JTree to give you some confidence... by that I mean knock you on your ass and remind you to be humble.
Very dabby but quite fun. My was too destroyed for this trip.. but hey I came for camaraderie not sends.
May not have gone as far right as I was supposed to now that I am reading the book. I followed the blue line... but the book says rightward AS FAR AS POSSIBLE. hmm. Oh well.
Crux is either be tall or trust some small feet.
Although I did a more direct finish than the little dashed yellow line on MP would imply, i liked the balancey solution I found to this problem.

Finally made it out to the Hanging Gardens! Such an awesome and actually dense set of boulders! Nothing blow you out of the water amazing, but nice to have ~20 boulders relatively close. And this side of the mountain is almost always in she shade! Bad feet to start this piece make it a little hard.
I had a TON of trouble with this one. Could be the shitty body settling in, but I had to really focus to figure out and execute fir the top. When your body feels bad top outs can be much scarier.

Crux jump start. lol. The features on this are amazing. Too bad they were all put in one place instead of spread out like "Shoot the moon" or "Twilight". Oh well cool features are still cool features. Shoutout Adenosine TriPhosphate, or rather username ATP on MP. His hand drawn topos make this area infinitely more enjoyable. Thank you kind sir for your efforts!

The spiciness to difficulty ratio  is a little high on this one. I mean its not scary but its scary for and easy climb if you know what I mean. I  am sad "The Golden Rule" broke but i feel like it still goes. It will be a ridiculous all points off sideways jump... but i think im into it!
This thing was rather surprising! Much better than expected and quite powerful.

I'm realizing my body is still feeling shitty for whatever reason. Could be the fact i've been nursing my sick sister all week... shes been Out Cold... heh heh, see what i did there? Don't worry her COVID test was negative, but I kind of think my body has been diverting some of my muscle power to fighting germs because Im still healthy.
Its amazing how round this boulder looks. Seriously looks like a large planet form several angles. This climb is aight.

From the sloper jug of "Final Round" just follow the lower lip all the way up and right, around the tree, and to the top. Rather enjoyable, even if the landing is a tad scary. Surprised this isnt on MP yet
Incredible feature and incredibly apt name. Loved the adventure.

Finally made it out to Lake Ramona!!! T'was just a quick little exploratory session, but had to at least do something new. Definitely checks the box for low ball classic!  Hats off to Aden Parker et al for reviving this amazing area from dormant obscurity. I cannot wait to get back out here with some peeps to get on all the classics! Ante Meridian and Ariel Charriot look amazballs.

msoftflash This has always felt so improbable. It boils down to one slopey crimp that you back flag off with one arm and hope the friction doesnt blow. Today it felt like piss. Was thinking V9 until today, because truth is its just friction dependent. Start as for "Data and Picard" make the cool left cross to the pocket as for "Follow Every Toast with a Song" but instead of going up, continue right across the face w/ a cool backflag match thing. Might be "breakable" for tall bois w/ high gaston
ascents.zlaggableName: Seven Six Four Three Seven Six Lock

ascents.comment: After climbing at Woodson enough... I have finally realized the boulder grades here are as wacky as Jim Carey on crazy pills. I read a discourse on what this climbs "boulder" grade should be and people argue passionately for as low as V4 and as high as V8! This thing is STOUT and will put most v7/v8 climbers on their asses. Its literally a forearm pump machine with a tricky top. That being said, incredible feature and my personal grade is V6. Can you deal with that!
Time to start my Woodson storm.

Sit Start. Start from your ass on a left hand slot crimp thing and right hand sloper. Two tough moves get you into the standard start. Certainly harder than the original but the original was pretty soft so this probably just solidifies the grade rather than bumps it.

What a LOVELY Thanksgiving! My brother wisely cancelled thanksgiving due to several illnesses across the family, so I way the rare opportunity and went climbing. I also did this thing without the Black Xeno by going straight up the prow and it felt like the same grade.

The overhanging "nose" up and right from King Nothing. Start right hand on crimp and jump for the side pull meat hook thing for your left. Slap your hands and choss your feet rightward to ultimately get yourself into the jugular tube feature. A direct press may be possible, as well as a left escape.  Most of Woodson's unexplored rock is either completely blank or perfect choss. This climb is more of the latter, but cool feature nonetheless.

Muchly a pointless silly climb. I did mantle the big fin to start which was kidna cool but its too easy, too forced and too in an awkward spot so it doesn't really have any redeeming qualities. Plus I had to top out into a bush then immediately downclimb which was.. well.. something.
So much tree growth I did not enjoy my time here.  This climb has literally pulled the shortest straw and will rarely be done.

From "I for an Eye" head directly west. You will pass a very obvious and very chossy prow. This is just passed the sideways tree on the same boulder as the chossy prow. Sit start low in two jugs and move up through a very cool groove feature with some huge side pulls. Move a little right to help ultimately move upward. How did I forget beer today!!! Bad llama.

From "I for an Eye" head directly west. This is the very obvious and very chossy prow. Hopefully as you pull on the holds you don't go out like the real Hanging Gardens and erase yourself from the face of the earth. Once nice perk when its this chossy, it kina sounds like rain while your are climbing which is a relaxing sound. Plus unlike real rain it isn't wet.

The sharp arete feature that comes out of a dang it hole to the right of "The River Tigris". This one fights back! Put me on my ass once and put me shoulder first into the back rock a few times. Very cool arete with a plethora of cool edges to crimp on. Techy feet make this one much more of a puzzle than it looks at first. Landing isn't great but just cover up the hole with a pad and you forget its there.
Sooooo easy. But that's part of its allure, not many truly easy things at woodson.

Yes!! This is the climb that made me seek Lake Ramona. Beyond fantastic with aesthetics in every category. Amazing rock and equally amazing view. Great movement AND I've unlocked a shorter friendly beta so now no excuses for not coming to LR. I love that the area overview for LR on MP still says: "The boulders on the hilltop west of Lake Ramona are enticing from afar but less appealing when you get closer. Mostly a nice destination for a morning hike." How wrong they were!

Def short, but still packs quite a bit of fun in its two moves. And that's not even mentioning the unbelievable top out on the most glorious quartz dike you have ever seen. Its like a full shelf of quartz (or whatever rock type you call these things).

Short and squeezy!! My Jam. Felt like basically one hard slap, but luckily this corridor stays pretty cool and had a breeze so friction was good. It's short and I'm good at squeezing so hard for me to accurately grade. I looked terrible on the top out. I think I did the worm.

This thing is INCREDIBLE; all variations are fantastic. I wonder how many people you could fit on this boulder at one time? Perfect angle with Pavlovian texture. Like seriously I'm drooling right now. Taller than you expect which just means more surface area to play! Honestly one of the most perfect slabs I have EVER been on. If you could somehow copy this and put it on an angle adjuster, it would be really awesome to see how steep the friction would hold.

Probably more like V2, but its tall and scary so Ill give you the bonus point. The Fractured Boulder continues to deliver. This climbs the crazy "s" like double angle change arete. One hard move down low gains you the second tier arete, and climbing eases significantly. Despite this entire boulder having incredible rock quality, the very apex of the boulder is shit and aptly also has shit. Bird shit that is. So take care on your journey! Yay me contributing to LR!

This climb is one of my favorite from the day! Such varied and fun movement on an incredibly gorgeous piece of rock. Only con is that it faces south so it gets hammered by that totally inconsiderate burning ball of gas in the sky. Shade felt cool, but while working this I felt like I was in the devils asshole. Honestly felt more like V6 or V7 to me but that could have just been due to that asshole thing, and the fact the ideal beta took a bit to find.
This felt hard for V2. The defining move is awesome, and the feature is unreal. I moved up the final arete keeping the toe hooks in which felt pretty dope.

Very aesthetic arete! And with a large start jug which always makes a climb more obvious and enjoyable.  Like its neighbor this climb has some incredible texture on the arete. The holds up and right feel a tad crumbly (through they are quite solid) and the movement is great. I have a huge agenda so very happy to have flashed.

As Aden says this is impossible to grade. We are both world class pressers so give us oranges and we will make you squished oranges. Quite enjoyable to work through thinking "oh this should be easy", to "holy shit this is impossible", to "oh wait.. I think I've got it", to finally "Woohoo". Cordellini Spandicterus please mail me five(5) united states dollars.

Honestly not sure if I started in the correct place, but I climbed something. Not as good as Babyface but similar. I started in a "V" like thing. left hand down pulling, right hand gastoning.  Quite hard first move. You definitely could start lower using a weird crimp undercling thing, but I kept hitting my battered shins so I opted out. Overall, the fracture boulder is a great place with quantity and quality.
Incredibly nice grippy arete for an enjoyable few moves of lie back! The texture is really quite fantastic.

Definitely cool, but until the trails get more trafficked PLEASE wear pants and save your legs from the bush whack bleeding and rawness that made showering quite unpleasant. I went from "Clean Slate" to here and it was basically all shrubs; luckily you can get here much easier from the main road. I would have liked this more if my legs weren't stinging but that being said, this is a RAD feature.! The crux felt like the top out not the stemming section. Good stemming is rare tho so very worth it!

As Aden says, "Unique and fun". Crazy jump start crux to get established on the rad "dish" holds. I hiked up here with two large organics, gallon of water, beer and other accoutrements which put my total pack weight at 57 lbs!! That's a lot of fitness!

How can something so big.... feel so hollow!? Fantastic to get out and soak up the sun and start my 2 week stint by killing a long overdue project. Woohoo! Time for a hot tottie! I sucked beside that, skin felt like it was made of butter but still sent and that's something.
The epic.... is finally over.
Pretty sure i tried this once 10 years ago. So cant flash. But ill take the m-soft-second-go. Yes, I still could not do Get Carter. Fuck me.
In case you are all wondering, no this is not in the guidebook. Its a weird one for sure...  classic!

Quite unique top out sequence! Feels impossible until you find it.... then it still takes a few foot picks and finger grease fires.. but well it goes! Life is still hard for me. Didn't even try today since chase made life look too easy.

lets just say... I lost the race.  Good work Shirley.. good work. Thank god for the really good finger jug, I was just so tired, ready to give up on life when my fingers found that amazingly ergo bucket.
That was NOT nice and easy. But at least I didn't run into a momma mountain lion and her three cubs!

Really nice. Definitely some spice. Those xeno knobs are great. I don't really like the name, I feel like this had a ton of potential.... although after thinking for the past 5 minutes I'm coming up blank so i guess thats that.

I remember watching Fanny Dingus do this the EPIC way, maybe.. 10 years ago. It scared me then, but I've grown a ball or two since then so today, I dared! I wish I had the hutspah to do the one arm lock off swing, but alas, I found some "trickery" as the book implied.  Really actually quite good with amazing rock and cool moves.

The book was VERY generous with stars on climbs on this boulder that are not Rio's crack. I bet 98.3% of people who have done Rio's crack don't even realize there are climbs to the right. They are all forced, and well, not great. With out any visible chalk or sweet nothings from andyliu84 this felt hard. Basically a huge dead point to a hold above the lip from a slightly awkward position.

Another one I've been afraid of ever since Guim crushed it when I was but a lad. Worked it today with some Powdered Toast Human or other delicious breakfast humanoid thing. We both crushed, so that was nice. Way more fun than I expected, definitely worth doing!

So stupidly soft. A good variant indeed, and after establishing RPC I understand more stupid ridiculous shit that is fun because well "Say Lah Vee". After matching the lip I just did a huge DP all the wat up and left to a good edge.
Best line on the boulder?

Took a while to find my beta. I did look at and andyliu84 before climbing today but I instantly forgot and all my data was meant to check on Cam Akers against the Patriots (He crushed). Anyway, I crushed Irange Crush, but I did it differently that andyliu84. From the good side pull I found a right toe cam and crossed from the first left side pull. DESERVES MORE ATTENTION. This thing is actually good.

I think this may be V8, but then again, may be not. The start is VERY hard to find. It says start on two pockets, but there is only one obvious pocket. The other one is garbage. This is a rare line where starting lower IS ACTUALY easier. Literally. If you start where Sabersonic does a simple cross leads to jugs.  Very hard pull off the ground, thanks heel toe cam, leads to jugs. There is a big throw but its to a jug so... soft?
EDIT: Shriley I started on the miserable pockets. First move crux.

Surprisingly... or not the top is the crux. Took me like 10 burns to figure it out. All my instincts lead to dabs so had to do some dumb ass shit.  But overall, this was surprisingly fun. It took me AGEs to find this because it is in a crazy crev-ass. Chase couldn't do.. and he did  Aquatic.. so I'm going to take 10 for this.
Lubba dubba dub dub!!! I did it boys! I did the thing! Not the thing over there, but this thing!

Mucho hardo! But also quite nice. I jumped for the wrong part of the lip and thought I might fall, break my body and be forced to drink all the beer i brought.... ah man i messed that one up, that sounds nice! Anyway, i really like rock creek, this climb is delicate and but also big. On my three pad descent from Compression Session (impossible) I happened upon this and had to do. I like trees and shade. I also love camels.

A climb as awesome as it is soft... and let me tell you tis pretty awesome! Got a solo session at rock creek today but third day on reeeeaaally is hard on the booty, by booty i mean body, you take a doodie with that? I'm a tired Grecian God that's for sure. Also Compression Session is really hard.  But back to the elephant, this climb is rad. Did the huge one arm swing dyno variant so yeah, I go big.

Wow. I'm the first one to log this? Means yalls are lil bitches. That right! This is an insanely aesthetic and obvious line. Oh landing? yeah that is a big pile of shit, and by shit i mean sharp uneven rocks.   Climbs pretty good but would be INCREDIBLE if it had a good landing. Fuck poached... consider me scrambled.

The grass was long and so I had to bust out ye old lawnmower: doing that for 10 burns will fuck you up.  I haven't been back to this boulder in 10 years. The Fang was literally the first climb (besides China Doll) that I did in bishop.
It was really cold. Waffleman setting a personal record for number of times someone can hit there head.
The EPIC is over. 69 attempts.

Wow. I've been intimidated by this for so gory darn long. People always said how soft this is and that frightened me! Could it really be that soft? What if I couldn't do it? Would people realize I'm actually weak? Thank God I did it today... this epic is over. Awesome line, only move i fell on was going to the pinch, that left slopey edge felt like shit. Same grade as the OG.

...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...and he SQUEEZED...

After finally sending Aquatic on an impressive final hurrah fuck it all greece man shirt off cold and he SQUEEZED magic I drank a beer went home to Highland ate some leftovers vacuumed drank more beer then came to lower canyon. Way more fun than expected. This thing is actually Unnamed V3**

I always wondered if this went before the new guide came out. Thanks Ian! Surprisingly fun with not so good landing. I used a finger lock and a toe cam, so you know its good. Felt pretty reachy, but what would I know I'm just a doctor. I brought a specially designed solar powered Black Light flood light set just for this occasion. It turned out really, really good. Can't wait to show you all the video.
This thing is actually really good. Its also only V4. Cool movement to choss. As long as you pull out not down you should be fine.
My favorite part about this boulder is the great beer holder hueco on the rock behind. Shout out that. some good features, but either i didnt climb it well, or it doesnt climb that well.

No fluttering hear on this? Just a note "Landing is pretty bad"? Wow V5 is hard these days. Seriously if anyone else does this they should probably upgrade. Its a basically a jump to a decent baseball sized hueco that you hold virtually one handed. Then the choss joins the party. I may be pooping on this but movement wise I though it was fun, i just wanted more points for it!
Better than I expected. Probably the closest chase came to falling on the boulder. Totally pulled an AKHIL. Yikes.

Quite Unique, and deserving of your respect. Another one I remember watching Fanny (and Miguel) do back in the day. Pretty sure they campused the crux, and back then I couldn't even do the clapper. Always cool to run full circle on something you used to thing was impossible, only to realize its soft.

Hardest line on the boulder. No question. A big round of applause is child's play. I cant believe Shirley didn't downgrade. Also Troy, did you really do this BEFORE Clapper? You cant flash if you had done the Clapper, sorry boy rules are rules. JK. Maybe you did it naked, I don't know. I also broke foot during my send burn. Not my foot mind you, the little piece of choss that is now a paper weight. Chaseypoo reaffirmed the grade, with a slightly worse foot about an inch to the right.

Incredible. Great holds all the way up on a beautiful rock, fairly tall, with great and easy top out. Was planning on climbing at Lake Ramona this weekend but had a few too many Pure Project Quads and Black Tuesdays on Christmas. Spent all Saturday recovering: Binged an anime called BNA and started a great Korean show called Sweet Home. I was going to climb more today, but pomegranate tree pruning took like 6 hours, what a monster tree! It had over 800 fruits this season!

Holy Poly there is a 'n' after the 'd'!? Who knew!? As a single boulder this is one of the better at Woodson, with a high quality V0 and two quality V7s (the second being the V4 'I shot the Sheriff'), its a fantastic little stop; plus its NEVER crowded. I unlocked a new school, long man beta to make this thing doper and probably easier. SUPER excited to come back and try the full sit, which definitely goes.

Short but incredible. Take any gym baby climber here and they will love it. Plus gym babies hate heights so its a win win. Who doesn't love some good ol' fashioned power on jugs. Felt quite easy for V4, but my finger skin was hurting like the dickens today so maybe its the only climb that i didn't have to grate/slice my poor babies. Will definitely add this to the LR intro circuit when showing someone the area for the first time.

I mentioned my poor finger babies right? Kept hitting a mental block on my finger skin pain and had trouble finishing this up. Whether it was just my finger skin or not, this felt harder than the OG. Not as good as the OG either, but a nice variation indeed.  The juggular feet make this quite enjoyable.

Might be slightly gimmicky but when nature give you gimmicks, you  gobble them up! Nature is so amazing. The movement is unique, fun and pretty much forced. Its hard to even set a climb in the easier grade range this cool. It's in a beautiful location with good rock quality, what else could you ask for!?

Its funny, this climb is also amazing, but when you compare it to the (Right) variation its slightly worse in each category. Still a MUST DO, but just funny that its incredible neighbor makes it feel less than it is. It is slightly less tall than the (Right) so that is maybe a perk. I am a happy man. You can see this climb / feature from the lake so that is something special too.

Perfection. Utter bliss. This is easily one of my top 5 favorite climbs of ALL TIME. Aesthetics are 6 / 5: perfectly cleaved face with a striking sharp arete, and even has that gory darn diving board feature! Movement is 6 / 5: looks improbably but as you start climbing, it feels oh so natural. Rock quality is 5 / 5. You could come to LR for this alone and you would leave happy.

I knew I was running on empty all day... but this is how I KNEW. know what I mean?  Fell at the top of a V3 because my body just completely gave out... took a super long break and managed to eek out the send but damn I'm destroyed. This is one of the most aesthetic climbs PERIOD. It doesn't even make sense how perfectly sculped the dike feature is.  Absolute must do.

Felt hard. Nice mantle into a few trust feet moves. My skin hurts so bad... climbing today may have been a bad idea.

Tried a rad line to the right of this trying to go directly up from a jug via some shallow pockets / mini crimps. Definitely goes but I will need more skin. Four of 'em to be exact.
Loved it. All the glory of Technical Difficulties ad a slightly cheaper price. Did you see that sky today? Talk about blue.

I don't even like crack, but this think is so epic and begs to be climbed. First move is rather painful but that's part of the appeal my dudes. I was honestly glad for something other that my tips to be screaming. This thing had awesome variety of movement of holds, but the steepness keeps it quite sustained. I ended up inverting to get one of my right hand jams in. It makes for a rather ludicrous but cool looking sequence.
It amazes me how jump starts are so enjoyable. The hold you jump to is quite pleasant and the ensuing slab is much more engaging than you expect! Good fun.

Wow. This thing seems like there are going to be a 100 betas, all of them good. Any climb that has perfect start holds at the base of a beautiful face is destined for greatness. A few razors on this one but ill spare you the finger skin complaints.
An easier variation of "Wax On" Start sitting low on the north east corner of the boulder with left hand in the good seam and right hand on a low sloper. Pull on and join "Wax On".

On the center of the East Face of the Grasshopper boulder.  Start on the super obvious jug and move right into a Gaston of your choice then  cross up to the awesome juggy pinch and top out, choosing the least chossy holds. Avoid most of the choss by moving right a tiny but.

Don't get caught with your beard in the mailbox, my dudes! This GEM of a climb is on the backside of Leisure Lagoon boulder: start to the right of the tree (narrowly not dabbing) with right hand under the shelf in an underling and left hand on the lowest jug at the back of the shelf. All holds above the first shelf are OFF which forces some fun moves out right, with a crux big throw to the big corner. Top out WITHOUT using any holds above the corner.. why? Because I said so.

Scandinavia has the best idioms. Back side of Leisure Lagoon, right hand low under cling, left hand lowest jug in first shelf. Go straight up on good holds. 

Finally stuck the last undone moves of two more of my contrived Data + Picard variations. Thought today would be a goose egg, but found this surprising feature. Honestly Leisure Lagoon bolder is dop.  RPC may be facing some access issues as I have heard a few accounts of rangers saying No Climbing. Hopefully ACSD can help!

I like the MP comment "Don't trash the rock". Lol. I don't think a run and jump is such an erosive event that we have to be worried about the rock crumbling after 3 people a year try this climb. Oh well, I do know their heart is in the right place. Run n Jumps could cause damage to the surrounding flora however so maybe that is worth worrying about. But then again no one does this. Anyway, this felt more like a waddle n jump. Not much run space and hard to aim your foot. Fun.

I think you could even sit start this! Better than the run n jump IMO b/c its actually climbing, if that makes sense. Eileen joined me today and flashed 2 V0s and a V1 (V2 on MP but she said it couldn't be that hard lol). So many open undone projects at Hanging Gardens! The Van Gogh Project ~V8, Polyglot Project ~V8, Wonder Boy Project ~V9, and the Project Euler Project ~V8. Much excite to get back here.

This is a harder intro into Little John's Crack, which means I got to run the gloriously tough V0 again. Could be V2? Probably depends on how low you start. Hilariously I saw some people from the top of the boulder who were trying to find little johns. I actually saw THREE groups of climbers today, all lost. The one group, a whole family, was looking for the Hanging Gardens.  I told them they only missed it by about a mile. The MP for the area can be a tad confusing for sure.

Holy poly I was afraid of a good egg today! I mean this is a whopping 0 points but that's not the same as a true goose egg. I failed AGAIN on 'Final Round' and 'I Shot the Sheriff' and started to get seriously worried when I was 6 burns into this V0... the crack closes up completely at the top op this boulder and you need to do a delicate slab move almost 20' up. Quite good, takes a while to trust yourself, but once you do it again feels like V0.

I was too tired to still be climbing. Was pumping out after any two moves. This climb is very un-Woodson-esque. Good holds and features, which make if feel pretty gym like. Kind of refreshing, and definite must do at the grade. Top is a jug.

This thing is many much more mega than I expected. Its like 25' of climbing and the top out is like 20+ feet up over a bad landing.  If MP gave it a 'R' I probably would have already sought it out.  Height = Aesthetic. Amazingly I ran into people at this boulder! What? Its so obscure. Damn covid. But cool to see peeps exploring their local crags. Cruxy lip traverse low into amazing highball arete. It is easy up top but 10/10 would never put a V3 climber on this.

OOOWheee! MSSGAS! Start as for Data and Picard but move diagonally up and left across the face. Another one I thought was crazy hard, but slowly found the easiest way to do each move, making it soft. Possibly too soft.  Could be V8... but until the Sandbox gets her to DG I'm taking it. Crux is sick, you get established on this sharp as hell left hand crimp, come over and match on something shitty then have to move out of it. Of the Federation starship my dudes!

Wow how did I miss this GEM.  On the back side of Garbage Compactor there is a good flat ledge about 1.5 feet off the ground. Use toe hook / bicycle shenanigans to establish then somehow navigate the lip without dabbing! An easier ~V3 variation uses a heel hook out right instead, but the best version starts with your body basically horizontal

The third generation start to the OG Tea Earl Grey Hot. FAs are rad, if no one is ever going to climb them, who can validate your V Point integrity? Could be V8 but that first move is quite difficult for big fingers. Start Right hand on the obvious crimp in the middle of the face, and left hand very low on a small crimp. Hard left hand move into the side pull of Data and Picard gets you into the start of V6, one more move gets you into the OG. One more move for 3 Points!? Seems questionable

This rock has definitely been pained over with rock colored paint to probably remove graffiti. Start on a pretty cool pinchy hold with crimps on either side, incredibly hard first move the way I did it (for V2 anyway, probably an easier beta I'm sure). After hitting that dope pinch it eases up significantly and simply follow up and right. Located above Garbage Compactor.

If this was more accessible this would be a classic V4 at Woodson. Its a little short but the moves are fun, the holds are good, and most importantly its SOFT! I want to take a moment to give my mom a big shoutout for reaching her goal and running 11 miles today in just over 11 minutes per mile! If I can still run 11 miles at 63 I will be a happy camper. Mom you are amazing! I am so proud of you and happy to have been able to help.

Great Climb! One of the moves feels like a foot levitation spell! Wingardriam Leviosa! Top out sent me plummeting a few times! Didn't scope well enough so I missed a key hold and was trying my best to grope up the incredibly rounded top with no holds. Almost went for the dignified beached whale but my pad wasn't quite in the right spot. Hard for 4.

I really hope I am not riddled with poison oak. Shout out Juneshine for their great booch, and hooking me up with a bonus delicious pack of some strawberry deliciousness. 

The first move of this climb is kid of silly. You have bonified bucked jugs so close but you start on the bad slopers. Not a bad move in any way but when jugs are so close it just feels a little deflated.

There is poison oak by these boulders! I didn't see it last week because twas dormant and there was another sticky look alike shrub! It is starting to bud, which is when the urushiol is the most ripe! Serious danger. I may be doomed honestly. I ran home and did the Tecnu Dance, so Tecnu Gods willing i washed it all off. This climb is the rock directly behind Terror Eyes. Left had sidepull, right hand any shitty sloperedge. One move to a cool sloper pinch thing and up!

Actually a pretty cool feature! The boulder is bigger than I expected from the picture. Classic Woodson making this hard for V2. I ended up using reach to make the final move a little easier but overall the movement was good. Top is NOT a jug.

First move is awesome, top out is meh. Bough some new Instincts today at Wilsons and while I love them, new rubber is like a new pair of underwear: at first its constricting, but then it becomes a part of you. On my top out rehearsal my foot blew like never before and I ate it hard. That sounded dirtier than I intended, but I fell to the ground.  Excited for them to become a part of me. Xavier's crux is still hard. Next year.

Probably not an FA but I don't want to forget. Just opposite swiss legends start on the small prow and after a campus or two rock yourself on top of the prow. Not much to warm up on out here because either its a 4 star climb or absolute choss.

If you were to judge this climb based on its average hold size.. it would easily be VB.  Luckily we grade climbs in a much more objective an accurate way by simply letting the FA-ist and guidebook writers embrace their inner assholes and give it whatever they are feeling. 

Great climb, and despite the high average hold size, aaverage hold distance, it still packs a punch. Pulled an AK on the crux. That move out right deceivingly hard.
This thing is actually awesome. Should probably have a fluttering heart. Its tall with good holds. Good for a beaten down boy.
ascents.zlaggableName: A Flake As Marvellous As You, Veruca
